00:03:31.960 --> 00:03:36.120
[Amit Varma]: Harsha, welcome to the scene in the unseen. Thank you.

00:03:36.120 --> 00:03:41.720
[Amit Varma]: Harsha, it's great to finally have you on the show. And before we start talking about

00:03:41.720 --> 00:03:45.600
[Amit Varma]: how cricket has evolved over the last 25-30 years that you've been part of the business,

00:03:45.600 --> 00:03:49.960
[Amit Varma]: tell me a little bit more about how you got into becoming a cricket journalist. I mean,

00:03:49.960 --> 00:03:53.920
[Amit Varma]: you weren't always a television guy, right? You started off as a lowly print person like

00:03:53.920 --> 00:03:59.320
[Guest]: me. I love the use of the word lowly, but long

00:03:59.320 --> 00:04:07.840
[Guest]: before the lowly print guy was a guy doing stuff on Yuvvani in Hyderabad. I was doing

00:04:07.840 --> 00:04:12.360
[Guest]: a little bit of radio commentary, actually. I did my first ball by ball broadcast when

00:04:12.360 --> 00:04:19.080
[Guest]: I was what 19 years old. It was a Ranji Trophy game. Learned a lot. Learned what people should

00:04:19.080 --> 00:04:24.120
[Guest]: not do and told myself when I become the senior broadcaster, these are things I will not do

00:04:24.120 --> 00:04:30.080
[Guest]: to younger people working with me. But yeah, print happened because I started traveling.

00:04:30.080 --> 00:04:35.160
[Guest]: I started touring and print was a source of revenue. And it was allowing me to cover up

00:04:35.160 --> 00:04:38.280
[Guest]: for other pursuits that were not going to pay me.

00:04:38.280 --> 00:04:40.200
[Guest]: And were you also a cricketer yourself when you started?

00:04:40.200 --> 00:04:44.400
[Guest]: I enjoyed playing cricket. I played about seven, eight years of cricket in Hyderabad.

00:04:44.400 --> 00:04:48.080
[Guest]: I played three years of senior division cricket, which means I was playing the A1 division

00:04:48.080 --> 00:04:53.400
[Guest]: every Sunday. I played two, three inter-college finals, got picked for my university. It's

00:04:53.400 --> 00:04:57.800
[Guest]: a very nice, convenient story for people to say, this guy didn't play cricket. I wish

00:04:57.800 --> 00:05:03.960
[Guest]: I could have shown them the four black marks on my thighs when we were still without thigh

00:05:03.960 --> 00:05:07.040
[Guest]: pads. And I can tell you, I know the pain.

00:05:07.040 --> 00:05:09.800
[Guest]: And you were a batsman, obviously, I presume.

00:05:09.800 --> 00:05:12.880
[Guest]: Everybody had to bat. We're playing on matting wickets. So batting wasn't such a challenge.

00:05:12.880 --> 00:05:17.060
[Guest]: But I started off being an off spinner for my school team. And then one day this kid

00:05:17.060 --> 00:05:21.720
[Guest]: turned up at the nets. So we're two of us bowling off spin for school for a year. And

00:05:21.720 --> 00:05:25.880
[Guest]: then one day this kid turns up and I looked at him and I said, dude, this guy's in a different

00:05:25.880 --> 00:05:29.120
[Guest]: league. So I started bowling leg spin and that's how that's what I bowled for the rest

00:05:29.120 --> 00:05:30.120
[Amit Varma]: of my life.

00:05:30.120 --> 00:05:31.120
[Guest]: Who was that kid? I thought the story is going to end in this.

00:05:31.120 --> 00:05:37.280
[Guest]: No, no, he played for India schools, actually. He went from the nets to our school nets to

00:05:37.280 --> 00:05:42.640
[Guest]: India schools in one year, the same year. Started off the school nets in six or eight

00:05:42.640 --> 00:05:47.080
[Guest]: months he was playing for India schools. So his name was Anant Vatsalya. Well, fantastic

00:05:47.080 --> 00:05:52.280
[Guest]: off spin. I mean, you just I mean, I've always been reasonably good at knowing what I can't

00:05:52.280 --> 00:05:56.840
[Guest]: do. So I looked at him and I said, you can't do this. So I started bowling leg breaks.

00:05:56.840 --> 00:05:59.320
[Guest]: And that's what I did till I finished university.

00:05:59.320 --> 00:06:05.440
[Amit Varma]: And how did you make the transition into full time journalism and then from print into television?

00:06:05.440 --> 00:06:10.160
[Guest]: Journalism because I was writing a little bit in Hyderabad. And then of course, I came

00:06:10.160 --> 00:06:15.880
[Guest]: to Mumbai and I wrote the odd piece here, the odd piece there. I was working with professional

00:06:15.880 --> 00:06:21.360
[Guest]: management group at the time. And while I was at Rediffusion Advertising before that,

00:06:21.360 --> 00:06:25.920
[Guest]: I had a couple of pieces published, including one in Debonair for Anil Dharkar, but it was

00:06:25.920 --> 00:06:26.920
[Guest]: about umpiring.

00:06:26.920 --> 00:06:27.920
[Guest]: I'm going to look up that issue.

00:06:27.920 --> 00:06:28.920
[Guest]: Yes, it was about umpiring.

00:06:28.920 --> 00:06:31.920
[Guest]: I read Debonair for the articles.

00:06:31.920 --> 00:06:39.320
[Guest]: Of course, everyone does. Everybody does. That's what they said about Leboy as well.

00:06:39.320 --> 00:06:44.920
[Guest]: And yeah, so one day Tariq Ansari calls me and said, would you want to do the England

00:06:44.920 --> 00:06:45.920
[Guest]: tour for us?

00:06:45.920 --> 00:06:46.920
[Guest]: And he's the owner of Midday.

00:06:46.920 --> 00:06:52.200
[Guest]: He then was the owner of Midday. Actually, when I left PMG, he said, we said, look, we've

00:06:52.200 --> 00:06:59.400
[Guest]: got three young women on our sports desk. Can you just help them make the pages? So

00:06:59.400 --> 00:07:04.680
[Guest]: come for two hours in the morning. That's it. And the three young girls all went on

00:07:04.680 --> 00:07:08.680
[Guest]: to have pretty good careers. One was Hemal Ashar, who worked for Midday. There's Prachwal

00:07:08.680 --> 00:07:12.760
[Guest]: Hegde, who still writes very well on tennis. And Sharda Agra, who I've grown to admire

00:07:12.760 --> 00:07:13.760
[Amit Varma]: ever since.

00:07:13.760 --> 00:07:15.560
[Guest]: She's a legend. And in fact, the other two as well.

00:07:15.560 --> 00:07:19.280
[Guest]: There you are. So those were the three young people there. So I'd go for two hours in the

00:07:19.280 --> 00:07:23.720
[Guest]: morning. And this was sort of March, April. And then in May, he said, do you want to do

00:07:23.720 --> 00:07:25.120
[Guest]: the England tour for us?

00:07:25.120 --> 00:07:26.120
[Guest]: Wow.

00:07:26.120 --> 00:07:28.960
[Guest]: I said, Tariq, why you and why not one of the women?

00:07:28.960 --> 00:07:33.840
[Guest]: Well, to be fair, they were very young. They were starting out. They were all excellent

00:07:33.840 --> 00:07:38.920
[Guest]: writers and they still are. But they were just starting out. So in fact, I did 1990

00:07:38.920 --> 00:07:43.800
[Guest]: by 91 Sharda was going around on tours. I said, Tariq, whatever you do, don't change

00:07:43.800 --> 00:07:49.760
[Guest]: your mind. And he said, so how much will it cost? I said, I have no idea. So I asked R.

00:07:49.760 --> 00:07:55.280
[Guest]: Mohan. And he said, whatever you do, don't accept less than 30 pounds a day. Okay. So

00:07:55.280 --> 00:08:01.640
[Guest]: Tariq was very generous. He gave me $100 a day, which was about 55, 56 pounds. But I

00:08:01.640 --> 00:08:06.120
[Guest]: had to organize all my travel, my stay, everything. When I write a book, I'll write the story

00:08:06.120 --> 00:08:14.080
[Guest]: about that. Lugging a manual typewriter with spare paper, carbon paper, spare ribbons,

00:08:14.080 --> 00:08:19.400
[Guest]: lugging it around everywhere. Keep typing and then Telex moved to fax. Now I'm sounding

00:08:19.400 --> 00:08:20.400
[Guest]: like I'm 200 years old.

00:08:20.400 --> 00:08:26.280
[Guest]: Who were the writers who kind of inspired you? The cricket writers?

00:08:26.280 --> 00:08:29.560
[Guest]: Not a lot. I mean, as a kid, we used to get Times of India in the afternoon. And we'd

00:08:29.560 --> 00:08:35.000
[Guest]: read K.N Prabhu's reports. But I, to be honest, the one, the couple of broadcasters I enjoyed

00:08:35.000 --> 00:08:40.800
[Guest]: were Dickey Ratnagar and Anand Sethalwad. And Anand Sethalwad had a lovely cadence about

00:08:40.800 --> 00:08:45.400
[Guest]: his voice and it would go lovely up and down and up and down. And I said, wow, that sounds

00:08:45.400 --> 00:08:50.440
[Guest]: nice. So those were the two. And for us, the biggest hero growing up was Ameen Sayani because

00:08:50.440 --> 00:08:53.520
[Guest]: we'd all listened to Binaka Geetmala.

00:08:53.520 --> 00:09:00.200
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, remarkable voice as well. And friendly voice. And from print to broadcast, how did

00:09:00.200 --> 00:09:01.200
[Amit Varma]: that come about?

00:09:01.200 --> 00:09:04.760
[Guest]: Actually, I'd done broadcast earlier because I was doing radio commentary in Hyderabad.

00:09:04.760 --> 00:09:10.720
[Guest]: Carried a cassette player to my league, senior division league game. I'm batting six, seven

00:09:10.720 --> 00:09:15.360
[Guest]: something. So my openers are batting, our openers are batting. And I recorded commentary

00:09:15.360 --> 00:09:19.920
[Guest]: on that, took it to All India Radio. It's a long story. But I did a little bit of radio

00:09:19.920 --> 00:09:26.400
[Guest]: commentary there. By the time I went to Ahmedabad, I had already done a few Ranji Trophy games.

00:09:26.400 --> 00:09:30.280
[Guest]: While I was in Ahmedabad, I did two one day internationals and a test match. So that came

00:09:30.280 --> 00:09:32.160
[Amit Varma]: before. That came before.

00:09:32.160 --> 00:09:35.640
[Amit Varma]: And was the nature of commentary different at that time? Like one of the shifts that

00:09:35.640 --> 00:09:40.000
[Amit Varma]: sort of happened was, you know, and this happened in television commentary. So maybe it's not

00:09:40.000 --> 00:09:44.640
[Amit Varma]: relevant to this. But, you know, back in the day, Richie Beno's advice, legend goes, used

00:09:44.640 --> 00:09:48.480
[Amit Varma]: to be that you only say something when you're really adding value. There's no need to describe

00:09:48.480 --> 00:09:52.640
[Amit Varma]: every shot because hey, the viewer can see that. And that apparently changed in your

00:09:52.640 --> 00:09:57.320
[Amit Varma]: time as a television, this thing where the brief was just filled every moment, keep talking,

00:09:57.320 --> 00:09:58.320
[Amit Varma]: don't don't stop.

00:09:58.320 --> 00:10:04.000
[Guest]: We had a soundtrack. I mean, if you paused as much as Beno, they'd put a commercial in.

00:10:04.000 --> 00:10:06.400
[Guest]: That's a great thing.

00:10:06.400 --> 00:10:13.040
[Guest]: Seriously. Radio commentary in India has disintegrated. Radio commentary in India had its highs in

00:10:13.040 --> 00:10:20.280
[Guest]: the 70s, 80s, 90s. There were some wonderful broadcasters, Korky, Original, even if you

00:10:20.280 --> 00:10:24.960
[Guest]: want to come down from Pearson, Surita and Dev Rajpuri and all the others down to Anand

00:10:24.960 --> 00:10:29.240
[Guest]: Settlewad, Dikki Ratnagar, Raj Singh was pretty good himself. There's some Hindi broadcasters,

00:10:29.240 --> 00:10:34.820
[Guest]: Suresh Sarai had a style of his own. So there were some really good radio broadcasters.

00:10:34.820 --> 00:10:38.200
[Guest]: And we haven't had one since. There's a couple of good ones. Prakash Vakankar is good, Sunil

00:10:38.200 --> 00:10:40.520
[Guest]: Gupta is good, but All India Radio is no.

00:10:40.520 --> 00:10:45.400
[Amit Varma]: And I guess part of the reason is a lot of the cricket lovers back then must have been

00:10:45.400 --> 00:10:49.640
[Amit Varma]: following cricket through radio. So they listen to radio. Today, I suppose very few people

00:10:49.640 --> 00:10:50.640
[Guest]: do.

00:10:50.640 --> 00:10:55.540
[Guest]: In India, not in Australia and England, where radio has held its own. The trick is to do

00:10:55.540 --> 00:11:02.640
[Guest]: on one medium, what a more powerful medium either cannot do or does not want to do. Television

00:11:02.640 --> 00:11:08.840
[Guest]: is a very powerful medium, but television is a very arrogant, it has a huge ego, television.

00:11:08.840 --> 00:11:17.480
[Guest]: Television will not be gentle and mild and polite and fun and informal, which radio can

00:11:17.480 --> 00:11:24.400
[Guest]: be. And so radio must do what television cannot do. But in India, we don't have radio commentary

00:11:24.400 --> 00:11:29.600
[Guest]: at all. And whatever there is, occasionally we wish there wasn't.

00:11:29.600 --> 00:11:33.520
[Guest]: And so literally just a few months back when I was on Crick Buzz and we're doing this,

00:11:33.520 --> 00:11:40.000
[Guest]: wanted to start Crick Buzz live and we said, we don't have a single second of footage.

00:11:40.000 --> 00:11:45.480
[Guest]: So we can't compete with television. So how do you then compete with television? You do

00:11:45.480 --> 00:11:52.120
[Guest]: everything that television will not do. So don't have breaks. Just three people sitting

00:11:52.120 --> 00:11:57.520
[Guest]: and chatting about cricket. And we chat about cricket for 25 minutes before the play. We

00:11:57.520 --> 00:12:01.560
[Guest]: talk about the team, we talk about the pitch, we talk who's playing, not playing, but it's

00:12:01.560 --> 00:12:07.200
[Guest]: an uninterrupted 25 minute conversation with loads of laughter. And we're getting a lot

00:12:07.200 --> 00:12:09.960
[Amit Varma]: of views. And one of the interesting kind of shifts

00:12:09.960 --> 00:12:14.040
[Amit Varma]: that happened in commentary itself before we get to talking about cricket in a general

00:12:14.040 --> 00:12:19.560
[Amit Varma]: way was that sometime around the mid 90s, there was this cult of celebrity where essentially

00:12:19.560 --> 00:12:23.880
[Amit Varma]: it became the rule that all commentators had to be ex-cricketers themselves and ex-test

00:12:23.880 --> 00:12:28.800
[Amit Varma]: cricketers are, you know, essentially brought in, like the logic would go that, hey, ex-cricketers

00:12:28.800 --> 00:12:32.040
[Amit Varma]: would have more insight about how to play the game, but they were essentially brought

00:12:32.040 --> 00:12:37.160
[Amit Varma]: in for celebrity value. And you were suddenly the only non ex-cricketer in those terms to

00:12:37.160 --> 00:12:43.480
[Amit Varma]: be in the frame. You know, how, how did that transition impact you? How did you respond

00:12:43.480 --> 00:12:47.400
[Guest]: to it? Luckily, I started before this happened.

00:12:47.400 --> 00:12:50.640
[Guest]: Exactly. So when this came around, I still remember

00:12:50.640 --> 00:12:57.320
[Guest]: my first proper television gig was the Hero Cup in 93. And by the time the Hero Cup came,

00:12:57.320 --> 00:13:01.320
[Guest]: I'd already done commentary in Australia. I'd been on BBC World Service. There weren't

00:13:01.320 --> 00:13:06.880
[Guest]: a lot of English voices that had worked on professional networks before. So I got to

00:13:06.880 --> 00:13:13.360
[Guest]: do the Hero Cup. I got to do a bit of television. By then only Gavaskar was around. By 94, Ravi

00:13:13.360 --> 00:13:18.760
[Guest]: Shastri came in. By the late 90s, Sanjay Manjrekar came in. So I was lucky that I was in there

00:13:18.760 --> 00:13:25.040
[Guest]: before. And I, well, I wasn't competing with them, which is why in that famous interview,

00:13:25.040 --> 00:13:30.000
[Guest]: I told Karan Thapar that I'm the non-striker. When I was batting, I always seemed to be

00:13:30.000 --> 00:13:32.280
[Guest]: batting with someone who was batting better than me.

00:13:32.280 --> 00:13:35.760
[Amit Varma]: And did that change your brief? Because I imagine when you do a radio commentary, you're

00:13:35.760 --> 00:13:39.080
[Amit Varma]: doing it essentially as equals. Everyone's got his opinions. You're just chatting, you're

00:13:39.080 --> 00:13:44.360
[Amit Varma]: shooting the breeze. But did your brief become in this case to be a sort of a sutradhar or

00:13:44.360 --> 00:13:48.960
[Amit Varma]: an enabler where you have to ask questions and get insights out of these stars rather

00:13:48.960 --> 00:13:54.200
[Guest]: than necessarily opine a lot on your own? It was not just inevitable. It was appropriate

00:13:54.200 --> 00:13:59.520
[Guest]: as well. Because I played school, college, university. I know what it is to hit the ball

00:13:59.520 --> 00:14:04.080
[Guest]: of a middle of a bat. I know the joy of holding a cricket, of catching a catch that shouldn't

00:14:04.080 --> 00:14:09.040
[Guest]: have been caught. But I have no idea of the pressure of going out to play on the first

00:14:09.040 --> 00:14:15.440
[Guest]: morning of a boxing day test. So if I tried, if I pretended that I knew, or if I said to

00:14:15.440 --> 00:14:21.020
[Guest]: somebody, you know what, his head is falling over when he plays the drive, it might be

00:14:21.020 --> 00:14:28.200
[Guest]: falling over. But I lay myself open to people saying, but how on earth do you know? And

00:14:28.200 --> 00:14:37.160
[Guest]: whether I know or don't know, I have to presume I don't know. But I found that I could get

00:14:37.160 --> 00:14:45.000
[Guest]: people to say what the average Joe wanted to. So therefore, willing, wittingly or otherwise,

00:14:45.000 --> 00:14:49.080
[Guest]: I became the voice of the common man in the in the commentary box. And they said, you

00:14:49.080 --> 00:14:52.760
[Guest]: know what, he asked the questions that we want to ask. So you're right. So that's how

00:14:52.760 --> 00:14:56.600
[Guest]: I became a facilitator. Radio commentary is completely different. Radio commentary is

00:14:56.600 --> 00:15:01.080
[Guest]: a million times easier. Easier. Or any day. Radio commentary is very, very easy because

00:15:01.080 --> 00:15:07.400
[Guest]: you can't go wrong. Because unless you lie, how do you go wrong on a radio broadcast?

00:15:07.400 --> 00:15:11.400
[Guest]: Because on radio broadcast, you're just telling people what you see. So I don't know if you

00:15:11.400 --> 00:15:16.080
[Amit Varma]: remember this. When I was when India toured Pakistan in 2006, I had come along, I was

00:15:16.080 --> 00:15:19.400
[Amit Varma]: covering that tour for the Guardian and also writing for Crick Info where I worked at the

00:15:19.400 --> 00:15:24.240
[Amit Varma]: time. And I also had this gig where I had to do like a 60 second update for BBC every

00:15:24.240 --> 00:15:28.840
[Amit Varma]: day, a number of times a day. And I was struggling with that. And I remember you were very kind

00:15:28.840 --> 00:15:32.080
[Amit Varma]: to actually come on your own and sit with me and give me a lot of great advice at the

00:15:32.080 --> 00:15:36.160
[Amit Varma]: time, which I still remember and appreciate. But one of the things that struck me when

00:15:36.160 --> 00:15:41.320
[Amit Varma]: I was trying to do that to give those 60 second updates, not live or anything, just 60 seconds,

00:15:41.320 --> 00:15:45.560
[Amit Varma]: is that as a writer, while I could always search for the right phrase or the right image

00:15:45.560 --> 00:15:50.520
[Amit Varma]: and avoid cliches, when I actually started speaking, the only thing which would come

00:15:50.520 --> 00:15:54.840
[Amit Varma]: into my head were cliches like, you know, like a tracer bullet and so on. Nothing else

00:15:54.840 --> 00:15:56.960
[Amit Varma]: would pop into my head. It became so...

00:15:56.960 --> 00:15:59.960
[Guest]: Not your fault. It's not your fault. You were listening to the wrong people.

00:15:59.960 --> 00:16:02.880
[Amit Varma]: Oh my God, you're actually saying that on record.

00:16:02.880 --> 00:16:07.400
[Guest]: I mean, look, cliches are cliches because they're true. That's why they are cliches

00:16:07.400 --> 00:16:08.520
[Amit Varma]: because they're true.

00:16:08.520 --> 00:16:12.560
[Amit Varma]: But on radio, that is an imperative that you have that you have to just keep talking. And

00:16:12.560 --> 00:16:17.680
[Amit Varma]: therefore, how do you find fresh ways of describing what is happening? You can't bring that sort

00:16:17.680 --> 00:16:22.440
[Amit Varma]: of that calculated, careful look that you can when you write some piece.

00:16:22.440 --> 00:16:29.760
[Guest]: Some people rehearse sentences. I was once told by Peter Baxter, who was the celebrated

00:16:29.760 --> 00:16:36.200
[Guest]: producer of Test Match Special, that a lot of Arlert's best lines, a lot of his best

00:16:36.200 --> 00:16:41.560
[Guest]: off the cuff lines were often the most rehearsed. They were often the most scripted. So sometimes

00:16:41.560 --> 00:16:45.320
[Guest]: you'd say, right, if this happens, I think I'll say that.

00:16:45.320 --> 00:16:50.720
[Guest]: So you need to ensure that you're not too eager to throw out the line because you've

00:16:50.720 --> 00:16:55.960
[Guest]: prepared it. It's almost like I've prepared for my civics exam, but they haven't asked

00:16:55.960 --> 00:17:00.240
[Guest]: me what I've prepared. So I'll say it nonetheless. You don't do that, but you know that if that

00:17:00.240 --> 00:17:06.480
[Guest]: comes that, that's what I'm going to say. So, but some people do that. I never did because

00:17:06.480 --> 00:17:10.240
[Guest]: it put too much pressure on you because you were constantly waiting for a situation to

00:17:10.240 --> 00:17:17.040
[Guest]: arrive for which your favourite line was best suited. And so sometimes you did a force fit

00:17:17.040 --> 00:17:21.720
[Guest]: and it never really worked. So the best thing to do is to go out there and say, you know

00:17:21.720 --> 00:17:27.640
[Guest]: what, I'm the most blessed person on the planet. So let me share my happiness with people.

00:17:27.640 --> 00:17:32.560
[Guest]: And that's how it comes. But the BBC World Service was one of the most valuable things

00:17:32.560 --> 00:17:39.840
[Guest]: in my life because it taught me time. So very often I'd be given 45 seconds to go and I'm

00:17:39.840 --> 00:17:44.320
[Guest]: doing this live in the middle of a game. So I'm sitting behind a commentary box using

00:17:44.320 --> 00:17:50.160
[Guest]: the producer's phone and making a collect call. You start these AT&T collect calls,

00:17:50.160 --> 00:17:54.600
[Guest]: do an AT&T collect call. Somebody in London picks it up, asks for the password. I give

00:17:54.600 --> 00:18:01.200
[Guest]: the password. They patch me on and now I'm live. I've got to hear the anchor there in

00:18:01.200 --> 00:18:06.440
[Guest]: the studio call my name. And of course, as he's saying, right, it's time to go now to

00:18:06.440 --> 00:18:11.080
[Guest]: India or wicket falls. And we don't live in soundproof commentary boxes in India. And

00:18:11.080 --> 00:18:16.000
[Guest]: so I can no longer hear the person at the other end. But to cut the noise, I would actually

00:18:16.000 --> 00:18:21.720
[Guest]: go under the table to try and cut the noise. But now the problem comes, you have only two

00:18:21.720 --> 00:18:27.520
[Guest]: hands. You have to have the watch in front of you because 45 seconds can mean 42 or 48,

00:18:27.520 --> 00:18:34.760
[Guest]: but it cannot mean 35 or 55. So you need the watch in one hand. You need to have the phone

00:18:34.760 --> 00:18:40.600
[Guest]: in the other. And you need to have the scorecard in front of you. And you need to be in a quiet

00:18:40.600 --> 00:18:44.560
[Guest]: place. You need four hands. And I wasn't going to, I wasn't a guard. I only had two hands.

00:18:44.560 --> 00:18:50.640
[Guest]: So and if you do that, if you if you try to jam the phone against your ear, then it doesn't

00:18:50.640 --> 00:18:55.760
[Guest]: sound right. Right. And then the wind would blow and so the paper would blow away. But

00:18:55.760 --> 00:19:01.720
[Guest]: I learned in all those times what 45 seconds was. Yeah. And to gather your thoughts so

00:19:01.720 --> 00:19:06.880
[Guest]: that on that watch in front of you when it goes to 35, it knows you mean, you know, you've

00:19:06.880 --> 00:19:14.000
[Guest]: got to start winding up by 41, 42, you're almost done. So I learned timing doing that.

00:19:14.000 --> 00:19:18.040
[Guest]: So if you're given 45 seconds, you say these are the only two points I can speak. I can't

00:19:18.040 --> 00:19:22.400
[Guest]: get the whole story of the match in. I prioritize. If he comes back and tells me, you know what,

00:19:22.400 --> 00:19:27.040
[Guest]: we didn't get through to the guy in Frankfurt. We've actually got 140 for you now. You've

00:19:27.040 --> 00:19:30.680
[Guest]: got to do 140. You do got to do 140. But in your mind, then you can say, OK, I've got

00:19:30.680 --> 00:19:35.920
[Guest]: a third or fourth thing I can include in the broadcast. So that was one of my biggest learnings.

00:19:35.920 --> 00:19:40.240
[Amit Varma]: I think in 2006, in fact, I was doing exactly that 45 second thing. And that same thing

00:19:40.240 --> 00:19:43.880
[Amit Varma]: would happen if something happened on the field in front of me while the call has come

00:19:43.880 --> 00:19:48.040
[Amit Varma]: through like a wicket fall, the someone hits a four or something changes. And I would just

00:19:48.040 --> 00:19:52.560
[Guest]: get extremely frustrated. That was actually an opportunity, because that means on a broadcast,

00:19:52.560 --> 00:19:56.960
[Amit Varma]: you could tell them live what was happening. So which is amazing. Yeah, I was I was too

00:19:56.960 --> 00:20:01.920
[Amit Varma]: naive at that time to kind of manage. So again, before we go on to the cricket, if you had

00:20:01.920 --> 00:20:07.880
[Amit Varma]: to sort of give young would be commentators on cricket in any medium that involves speaking

00:20:07.880 --> 00:20:14.520
[Guest]: advice, what would you say? Well, peculiarly, the first thing I would say is pick all pieces

00:20:14.520 --> 00:20:19.640
[Guest]: of ego in your brain and trample them to death. Because if you have an ego, you've got no

00:20:19.640 --> 00:20:26.180
[Guest]: chance in life. I meet a lot of young presenters who want to be primetime television heroes

00:20:26.180 --> 00:20:31.360
[Guest]: on day zero, right? It's not going to happen, you are going to make mistakes. And the best

00:20:31.360 --> 00:20:38.060
[Guest]: time to make mistakes is when nobody's watching. So give yourself pre run G trophy, finish

00:20:38.060 --> 00:20:43.480
[Guest]: making all your mistakes, then when you're ready, you're ready. So actually, I tell everybody

00:20:43.480 --> 00:20:48.260
[Guest]: to start doing audio, don't do television, don't do camera, because the camera is this

00:20:48.260 --> 00:20:52.360
[Guest]: big enticing thing that makes you look at it a certain way. And then it causes you to

00:20:52.360 --> 00:20:57.040
[Guest]: freeze. Right. One of the things I always tell people is why do models always make bad

00:20:57.040 --> 00:21:01.880
[Guest]: anchors? Because the models are so obsessed with the angle and the light and the way they

00:21:01.880 --> 00:21:07.060
[Guest]: look. But then what are you going to say? And being a good anchor to some extent, does

00:21:07.060 --> 00:21:11.200
[Amit Varma]: it just involve just relaxing and letting things happen rather than, you know, being

00:21:11.200 --> 00:21:16.700
[Guest]: conscious and maintaining exactly that pose in this expression. The beauty of live television

00:21:16.700 --> 00:21:21.300
[Guest]: is you don't even have time to think which pose you're in a way you are. I've had water

00:21:21.300 --> 00:21:26.660
[Guest]: thrown on me on a live telecast. I've had people yanking me in all directions. The advantage

00:21:26.660 --> 00:21:31.480
[Guest]: of the live telecast is you don't have to be perfect. Right. So I often tell people

00:21:31.480 --> 00:21:37.560
[Guest]: a live telecast anchor is like a fighter pilot. He just he just lands, picks up goes. Whereas

00:21:37.560 --> 00:21:42.900
[Guest]: a recorded anchors, if you're doing Indian Idol, or you're doing Kaun Banega Crorepati,

00:21:42.900 --> 00:21:48.380
[Guest]: then you're like a passenger liner, right? Everything is correct. And someone's opening

00:21:48.380 --> 00:21:52.300
[Guest]: the wine and business class and someone just walking down and someone's showing you to

00:21:52.300 --> 00:21:59.140
[Guest]: that place. And the livery is perfect. No, in live telecast, no. I mean, there are days

00:21:59.140 --> 00:22:04.260
[Guest]: when my armpits have been soaked. There are days where I'm wearing a jacket, not because

00:22:04.260 --> 00:22:08.940
[Guest]: I want to wear a jacket because I sweated so much I could squeeze my shirt. There are

00:22:08.940 --> 00:22:13.100
[Guest]: days when I've got droplets falling off my eyes, but that's okay. It's live television.

00:22:13.100 --> 00:22:17.580
[Guest]: But if you start to think, Oh, how am I looking? Is my makeup coming off a little bit, then

00:22:17.580 --> 00:22:21.900
[Guest]: your focus is not on communication. And the reason you're there is to communicate not

00:22:21.900 --> 00:22:26.660
[Guest]: not to worry about how you look. If if the way people looked made them successful, then

00:22:26.660 --> 00:22:30.100
[Guest]: I want to pass the first exam. So it doesn't matter.

00:22:30.100 --> 00:22:34.180
[Amit Varma]: And obviously the first responsibility of a broadcaster of a TV commentator is obviously

00:22:34.180 --> 00:22:38.940
[Amit Varma]: towards the viewers. But at the same time, did you also feel that as time went on and

00:22:38.940 --> 00:22:42.940
[Amit Varma]: you know, players became more powerful, that there was also another audience in play that

00:22:42.940 --> 00:22:46.780
[Amit Varma]: you had to be conscious about what you can or cannot say about some player that you have

00:22:46.780 --> 00:22:52.220
[Amit Varma]: to moderate yourself in terms of, you know, maybe pissing the board off or whatever. Do

00:22:52.220 --> 00:22:54.260
[Amit Varma]: those considerations come into play?

00:22:54.260 --> 00:23:00.540
[Guest]: I was I was blessed amid that my best years in television and I'm saying this very confidently

00:23:00.540 --> 00:23:05.060
[Guest]: because I know they've gone that my best years in television coincided with the best set

00:23:05.060 --> 00:23:09.100
[Guest]: of human beings that played cricket. There was a Tendulkar, there was a Lakshman, there

00:23:09.100 --> 00:23:14.020
[Guest]: was a Dravid, there was a Kumli, there was a Srinath, there was a Ganguly. And I broadcast

00:23:14.020 --> 00:23:18.940
[Guest]: through their entire career. There was not one day, not one day that one of them came

00:23:18.940 --> 00:23:22.940
[Guest]: up and said, you know what, I didn't like what you said. I can't say the same about

00:23:22.940 --> 00:23:24.180
[Guest]: the generation that followed.

00:23:24.180 --> 00:23:28.780
[Amit Varma]: I understand. And I won't push you on to that. Let's move on to the cricket.

00:23:28.780 --> 00:23:33.340
[Guest]: It also happened because of social media. Because of social media, there's people saying

00:23:33.340 --> 00:23:37.420
[Guest]: all kinds of things and people start to believe what they see on social media.

00:23:37.420 --> 00:23:41.700
[Amit Varma]: Is it something you're comfortable talking about? Because otherwise I won't push you.

00:23:41.700 --> 00:23:48.900
[Guest]: Suppose, very simply, suppose I've said, oh, he played a poor shot on 99. Now, it's all

00:23:48.900 --> 00:23:54.260
[Guest]: right to say that. Somebody on social media will then start a rant saying, oh, you don't

00:23:54.260 --> 00:23:58.300
[Guest]: like him. That's why you said that. Like, for example, I've been told that I'm a Mumbaikar

00:23:58.300 --> 00:24:04.460
[Guest]: and so I reserve my best expressions for Tendulkar. And I'm told you're from Hyderabad. So you

00:24:04.460 --> 00:24:07.980
[Guest]: sound far better when you're talking about Lakshman. So people will read what they want

00:24:07.980 --> 00:24:12.700
[Guest]: to. When they read that and then it starts getting a life of its own, then it reaches

00:24:12.700 --> 00:24:19.140
[Guest]: somebody. And then people start to misinterpret these things. So the arrival of social media

00:24:19.140 --> 00:24:23.260
[Guest]: has added a lot of toxicity to communication. And so you've got to be extra careful with

00:24:23.260 --> 00:24:25.300
[Amit Varma]: the arrival of social media.

00:24:25.300 --> 00:24:33.100
[Amit Varma]: Let's kind of move on to the cricket now. It's my sense that over the time that you've

00:24:33.100 --> 00:24:38.820
[Amit Varma]: been in cricket, the 25-30 years or so, there have been two major inflection points which

00:24:38.820 --> 00:24:43.420
[Amit Varma]: have changed cricket. I mean, tell me if you agree and if you want to add to these or add

00:24:43.420 --> 00:24:49.220
[Amit Varma]: caveats. One is the television explosion, the satellite television explosion in the

00:24:49.220 --> 00:24:54.220
[Amit Varma]: 90s, which just changed the commerce of the game entirely and made India the hub of world

00:24:54.220 --> 00:24:59.940
[Amit Varma]: cricket and made players into superstars and everything changed there. And the second would

00:24:59.940 --> 00:25:05.260
[Amit Varma]: be in a slightly different sense, the T20 IPL revolution that had the same kind of commercial

00:25:05.260 --> 00:25:10.620
[Amit Varma]: impacts, but also it changed the game by changing the incentives for the players, what kind

00:25:10.620 --> 00:25:15.780
[Amit Varma]: of cricket they were learning and refining and therefore brought forward a new breed

00:25:15.780 --> 00:25:20.100
[Amit Varma]: of players in a manner of speaking, which changed the grammar and language of the other

00:25:20.100 --> 00:25:25.260
[Amit Varma]: forms of the game like Test cricket, which I argued in a column which got a lot of flack

00:25:25.260 --> 00:25:29.580
[Amit Varma]: recently that perhaps Test cricket is destined to die in these modern times.

00:25:29.580 --> 00:25:34.580
[Amit Varma]: I can see why you got flack on that one. But would you broadly say that, I mean, we'll

00:25:34.580 --> 00:25:38.180
[Guest]: come to that, you know, when we come to that. I'm a strong point of view on that. You might

00:25:38.180 --> 00:25:43.100
[Amit Varma]: be in agreement. So yeah. Yeah. So we'll come to that towards the end. But in general, do

00:25:43.100 --> 00:25:46.420
[Amit Varma]: you agree that these are the two main inflection points that we should be focusing on?

00:25:46.420 --> 00:25:51.220
[Guest]: Yes, the first of those was not as much a cricketing inflection point as a point that

00:25:51.220 --> 00:25:57.180
[Guest]: was forced upon India through the terrible financial position we were in, right? We had

00:25:57.180 --> 00:26:02.020
[Guest]: three weeks of foreign currency reserves, when Narsimha Rao became Prime Minister of

00:26:02.020 --> 00:26:08.500
[Guest]: India. And I mean, it's fashionable not to talk about Narsimha Rao as it's fashionable

00:26:08.500 --> 00:26:14.660
[Guest]: not to talk about why we raid D as it's fashionable not to talk about the self aggrandizing show

00:26:14.660 --> 00:26:19.460
[Guest]: ponies or whatever the expression is. But because of that, we had no choice but to open

00:26:19.460 --> 00:26:25.180
[Guest]: the economy, the economy opened. The biggest beneficiary of that was Tendulkar, because

00:26:25.180 --> 00:26:28.940
[Guest]: the Pepsi's of the world came in. I think Pepsi is actually a pretty good inflection

00:26:28.940 --> 00:26:33.820
[Guest]: point, even though it's a brand that we talk about. But Pepsi came in with big budgets.

00:26:33.820 --> 00:26:39.440
[Guest]: And as a result, overseas television networks came into India. And Dalmia and Bindra sat

00:26:39.440 --> 00:26:44.660
[Guest]: and questioned Doordarshan. And Doordarshan was doing a magnificent job of killing cricket.

00:26:44.660 --> 00:26:49.300
[Guest]: Right. It kills all sport. It kills all sport. The coverage was banal. It was boring. The

00:26:49.300 --> 00:26:54.420
[Guest]: commentators you I mean, you knew somebody I shouldn't say that because I did get a break

00:26:54.420 --> 00:26:58.300
[Guest]: on Doordarshan. I cut my teeth in All India Radio. I made all my mistakes. I owe them

00:26:58.300 --> 00:27:05.060
[Guest]: a debt. But there was no deep inner desire for excellence. If you're writing a book and

00:27:05.060 --> 00:27:11.420
[Guest]: you want to win a major literary prize, and you say, let me just write 200 words at anything

00:27:11.420 --> 00:27:14.740
[Guest]: goes, you don't win a prize like that you must have this great passion to be the best

00:27:14.740 --> 00:27:19.060
[Guest]: you can be. And Doordarshan wasn't that it still isn't it cannot be that. The incentives

00:27:19.060 --> 00:27:22.420
[Guest]: are simply not tailored towards that. So you cannot get the best talent for the prizes

00:27:22.420 --> 00:27:27.620
[Guest]: they were offering. So I can understand the limitations they had. But suddenly we got

00:27:27.620 --> 00:27:32.620
[Guest]: world class television producers coming to India. And that made a difference for people

00:27:32.620 --> 00:27:37.180
[Amit Varma]: like me. And what also you know, happened in that period just prior to all this was

00:27:37.180 --> 00:27:42.340
[Amit Varma]: that Doordarshan actually used to demand money to broadcast matches. Yes. And Dalmia and

00:27:42.340 --> 00:27:46.100
[Amit Varma]: Bindra kind of turned this around by just following through on the common sense that

00:27:46.100 --> 00:27:50.260
[Amit Varma]: hey, why should we pay you money to broadcast you should pay us because look at the...

00:27:50.260 --> 00:27:55.100
[Guest]: There's a fantastic story about that, that Amrit Mathur told me about and Amrit was close

00:27:55.100 --> 00:28:00.940
[Guest]: to the board at the time, when South Africa first came to India in late 1991. And the

00:28:00.940 --> 00:28:05.580
[Guest]: SABC was a South African broadcasting corporation asked the question of the BCCI that nobody

00:28:05.580 --> 00:28:11.740
[Guest]: ever asked before, how much do you want for rights? And they said, Oh, we're supposed

00:28:11.740 --> 00:28:18.340
[Guest]: to get money for this. And Amrit tells the story, they said, chalo itna puchte. And then

00:28:18.340 --> 00:28:23.940
[Guest]: somebody said, let's ask them, no, they might give more. And as it turns out, SABC offered

00:28:23.940 --> 00:28:30.340
[Guest]: more than the BCCI thought they could ever get. Wow. And that is when they realised that

00:28:30.340 --> 00:28:36.300
[Guest]: that the sitting on a property that can be monetised. And that is how they went in revolt

00:28:36.300 --> 00:28:41.180
[Guest]: against Doordarshan. And then it led to the famous court case and the legal situation

00:28:41.180 --> 00:28:46.460
[Guest]: of who owns the airwaves, and whether uplinking is a fundamental right or no, whether anyone

00:28:46.460 --> 00:28:52.220
[Guest]: can uplink or no. And it changed the world of live broadcast. But it also because it

00:28:52.220 --> 00:28:57.020
[Guest]: brought in all these networks, ESPN came in 95, Prime Sports was around and became Star

00:28:57.020 --> 00:29:02.060
[Guest]: Sports. It allowed people like me a break. So I often tell people that across, well,

00:29:02.060 --> 00:29:06.820
[Guest]: might be on different points on a logarithmic scale, but the way Tendulkar benefited from

00:29:06.820 --> 00:29:12.460
[Guest]: liberalisation in my profession, I benefited similarly, even if the magnitude of the opportunity

00:29:12.460 --> 00:29:17.140
[Guest]: was vastly different, but we all benefited from that. I mean, you, me, everyone, all

00:29:17.140 --> 00:29:23.180
[Guest]: of India that was reasonably young at that time, benefited enormously from that one moment

00:29:23.180 --> 00:29:29.740
[Guest]: when Manmohan Singh and Narsimha Rao and all the people in North Block or South Block,

00:29:29.740 --> 00:29:33.460
[Amit Varma]: whatever it's called, sat together and produced that budget. Right. And I mean, obviously

00:29:33.460 --> 00:29:37.780
[Amit Varma]: under the, I mean, they were forced to by the IMF and all that, just the way it was.

00:29:37.780 --> 00:29:42.780
[Amit Varma]: But regardless of that, that changed all our lives. One of the interesting ways in which

00:29:42.780 --> 00:29:46.460
[Amit Varma]: I tell people it changed is, I mean, there are really two ways it seems to me that that

00:29:46.460 --> 00:29:52.900
[Amit Varma]: kind of changed. One was that liberalisation itself empowered people in small towns and

00:29:52.900 --> 00:29:57.020
[Amit Varma]: middle class India to take up the game and the sort of the demographic representation

00:29:57.020 --> 00:30:01.660
[Amit Varma]: of the people who could play cricket and aspire to, you know, playing for India and all of

00:30:01.660 --> 00:30:06.340
[Amit Varma]: that changed, which is why you had more and more cricketers in the Northeast coming from

00:30:06.340 --> 00:30:10.540
[Amit Varma]: the smaller towns. And another way in which your broadcasting directly contributed was

00:30:10.540 --> 00:30:16.820
[Amit Varma]: that a lot more people would watch the game and be exposed to values of modern cricket.

00:30:16.820 --> 00:30:21.420
[Amit Varma]: Like every time you praise a John T. Rhodes for doing what he's doing, or you praise people

00:30:21.420 --> 00:30:25.780
[Amit Varma]: for running between wickets well and grounding their bat properly, those values are filtering

00:30:25.780 --> 00:30:29.580
[Amit Varma]: down into the young 12 year old, 13 year olds who are watching.

00:30:29.580 --> 00:30:33.500
[Guest]: It did, Rahul Dravid often tells me that the spread of television, that television became

00:30:33.500 --> 00:30:39.500
[Guest]: the best coach a small town kid could get, because there he was watching Tendulkar and

00:30:39.500 --> 00:30:45.340
[Guest]: he was hearing Benno and Greg and Gavaskar and everybody talking about it. And so it

00:30:45.340 --> 00:30:50.980
[Guest]: almost became like, like the coach he could never have got, because initially, cricket

00:30:50.980 --> 00:30:55.660
[Guest]: knowledge was confined to the cities. It was in Mumbai, it was in Bangalore, it was in

00:30:55.660 --> 00:30:59.140
[Guest]: Delhi, it was in Chennai, it was in Hyderabad, whatever you look at where the 1983 World

00:30:59.140 --> 00:31:06.980
[Guest]: Cup team came from. By the time, well, Saiwag started, Zaheer started, all these guys, the

00:31:06.980 --> 00:31:11.100
[Guest]: small town boys started feeling empowered, because they had learned a lot of their cricket

00:31:11.100 --> 00:31:16.140
[Guest]: from television. And then you saw the revolution that led to 2007, you saw the fire of small

00:31:16.140 --> 00:31:21.100
[Guest]: town India coming through. And now we are well into that revolution to the extent that

00:31:21.100 --> 00:31:27.540
[Guest]: the old nursery of Indian cricket, which was the middle income Mumbai boy, who became the

00:31:27.540 --> 00:31:30.500
[Guest]: India cricketer, will never ever play for India again.

00:31:30.500 --> 00:31:35.580
[Amit Varma]: I mean, you could argue the middle income Mumbai boy, quite naturally has a lot of things

00:31:35.580 --> 00:31:40.660
[Amit Varma]: competing for his time, a lot else to aspire to which he can realistically achieve. While

00:31:40.660 --> 00:31:45.060
[Amit Varma]: this for many small town kids, cricket is still, you know, that dream out there.

00:31:45.060 --> 00:31:50.420
[Guest]: It is because the upside is huge, and the downside is minimal. For the middle class

00:31:50.420 --> 00:31:56.900
[Guest]: boy who has to get the 10th standard and 12th standard marks, the downside of not making

00:31:56.900 --> 00:32:01.220
[Guest]: it in cricket is huge. The upside is, the kind of money now is huge anyway, but the

00:32:01.220 --> 00:32:02.740
[Guest]: downside is huge as well.

00:32:02.740 --> 00:32:07.700
[Amit Varma]: I mean, you wrote a very moving book on Azharuddin and it kind of strikes me as, you know, a

00:32:07.700 --> 00:32:12.500
[Amit Varma]: poignant thing that he just got his timing all wrong in the sense, had he come into cricket

00:32:12.500 --> 00:32:17.260
[Amit Varma]: 10 years later, he would not have needed to or been tempted to go into those kinds of

00:32:17.260 --> 00:32:23.820
[Amit Varma]: directions, which, you know, cast a blemish on his, you know, if he was like born in 1997

00:32:23.820 --> 00:32:28.740
[Amit Varma]: and grew up in the IPL age and all that he could have just, yeah, who knows? There's

00:32:28.740 --> 00:32:34.060
[Guest]: it is I mean, inadvertently, we've stumbled onto one of the biggest problems of the IPL,

00:32:34.060 --> 00:32:40.180
[Guest]: which is, how do you get these children coming from lower to lower middle class households

00:32:40.180 --> 00:32:44.980
[Guest]: to feel comfortable with wealth and fame. And it's something that affected people around

00:32:44.980 --> 00:32:48.980
[Guest]: that time as well, match fixing and all that thing that happened, which, given our legal

00:32:48.980 --> 00:32:52.420
[Guest]: system, it's ridiculous, it was never ever proved. So we can't even say that it happened

00:32:52.420 --> 00:32:58.340
[Guest]: because it was it was never proved. But we found that there are people who could get

00:32:58.340 --> 00:33:04.940
[Guest]: swayed by the riches and other temptations on offer. And hopefully now that that won't

00:33:04.940 --> 00:33:09.380
[Guest]: happen, but there's so much money in the game now that it is something we need to worry

00:33:09.380 --> 00:33:14.380
[Guest]: very, very carefully, we need to be very concerned about it. There are people who don't know

00:33:14.380 --> 00:33:20.700
[Guest]: what 10 lakhs is, who are getting 200 lakhs for playing six weeks. And suddenly their

00:33:20.700 --> 00:33:29.180
[Guest]: family is now saying, okay, how do we get them to stay focused on cricket, keep practicing

00:33:29.180 --> 00:33:33.340
[Guest]: their skills, and not say I'll come and bowl four overs, pick up my paycheck and go because

00:33:33.340 --> 00:33:37.020
[Amit Varma]: that paycheck goes as quickly as it comes. And you've known cricketers from before the

00:33:37.020 --> 00:33:41.420
[Amit Varma]: inflection point of the mid 90s or the early 90s or whatever. And you've known them afterwards

00:33:41.420 --> 00:33:45.260
[Amit Varma]: and money has come into the game. And also because of mass media, there's suddenly superstars

00:33:45.260 --> 00:33:49.700
[Amit Varma]: at an unprecedented level, including young people who've come from small towns and out

00:33:49.700 --> 00:33:53.100
[Amit Varma]: of nowhere, they are superstars, you know, like the Sehwags and the Yuvraj and the Zaheer

00:33:53.100 --> 00:33:57.140
[Amit Varma]: and all those guys that first generation of small town kids in a sense, I suppose.

00:33:57.140 --> 00:33:58.140
[Unknown]: Harbhajan.

00:33:58.140 --> 00:34:02.300
[Amit Varma]: Harbhajan. How did that change them? What did you see? Like, was it harder to cope with

00:34:02.300 --> 00:34:05.260
[Amit Varma]: that? Did it get to their head? Did it affect their cricket?

00:34:05.260 --> 00:34:10.100
[Guest]: They were very lucky that I mean, Harbhajan had Anil Kumble, for example, a Sehwag had

00:34:10.100 --> 00:34:16.340
[Guest]: a Tendulkar, which is why in almost everywhere that I go, I talk about the huge debt that

00:34:16.340 --> 00:34:22.580
[Guest]: Indian cricket owes to those group of six or seven players, Ganguly, Tendulkar, Laxman,

00:34:22.580 --> 00:34:28.940
[Guest]: Dravid, Srinath, that group of people who came up from fairly similar backgrounds, because

00:34:28.940 --> 00:34:33.740
[Guest]: cricketers used to come from middle class families and the middle class is still a storehouse

00:34:33.740 --> 00:34:34.740
[Amit Varma]: of values.

00:34:34.740 --> 00:34:35.740
[Guest]: So they were grounded middle class guys.

00:34:35.740 --> 00:34:41.940
[Guest]: A storehouse of values. The Indian middle class is a storehouse of the right values.

00:34:41.940 --> 00:34:46.700
[Guest]: And they all came up from there. You only had to see Rahul Dravid's father to know that

00:34:46.700 --> 00:34:50.740
[Guest]: you can offer Rahul Dravid the greatest temptation in the world and he won't be able to look

00:34:50.740 --> 00:34:52.800
[Guest]: his father in the eye.

00:34:52.800 --> 00:34:59.180
[Guest]: You knew that, I mean, someone once told me if Tendulkar accepts money, then what is left?

00:34:59.180 --> 00:35:03.500
[Guest]: And I said, go and look at Tendulkar's family. There's no way on earth that can happen. If

00:35:03.500 --> 00:35:08.660
[Guest]: Anil Kumble took money to perform badly, for one, he wouldn't be Anil Kumble, for two,

00:35:08.660 --> 00:35:11.140
[Guest]: I wouldn't be broadcasting.

00:35:11.140 --> 00:35:17.060
[Guest]: So that group of people, and so the newcomers coming in could see how grounded they were

00:35:17.060 --> 00:35:22.060
[Guest]: and how they were learning and how they, so that generation was very influenced.

00:35:22.060 --> 00:35:26.460
[Guest]: The new generations, the Harbhajans, the Zaheers, all these guys coming in were very heavily

00:35:26.460 --> 00:35:29.780
[Guest]: influenced by this core group of seniors.

00:35:29.780 --> 00:35:33.780
[Amit Varma]: And I'm just kind of thinking aloud. I mean, we often wonder about why in Pakistan there

00:35:33.780 --> 00:35:37.940
[Amit Varma]: is so much churn among players that, you know, people come and they go and very often you

00:35:37.940 --> 00:35:41.460
[Amit Varma]: see the celebrity and the money affecting them and they change behavior and they also

00:35:41.460 --> 00:35:46.140
[Amit Varma]: seem to be more susceptible to those kinds of influences.

00:35:46.140 --> 00:35:51.300
[Amit Varma]: And one possibility could be that for a long time in Pakistan, they said there is no middle

00:35:51.300 --> 00:35:52.300
[Amit Varma]: class.

00:35:52.300 --> 00:35:56.900
[Amit Varma]: There is just your upper tier of really privileged elites and then everything is less than middle

00:35:56.900 --> 00:35:57.900
[Amit Varma]: class.

00:35:57.900 --> 00:36:01.980
[Amit Varma]: And therefore, perhaps those typically middle class values which you're talking about simply

00:36:01.980 --> 00:36:02.980
[Amit Varma]: weren't there.

00:36:02.980 --> 00:36:07.660
[Guest]: It could be under Imran Khan, I can assure you, absolutely nothing would have happened

00:36:07.660 --> 00:36:10.820
[Guest]: because Imran was one of the rare cricketing statesmen.

00:36:10.820 --> 00:36:14.540
[Guest]: I don't know how good he is as a political leader, but if Imran was in charge of world

00:36:14.540 --> 00:36:16.980
[Guest]: cricket, cricket would be very different.

00:36:16.980 --> 00:36:21.940
[Guest]: And so a lot of people grew under him and they were scared of him.

00:36:21.940 --> 00:36:26.220
[Guest]: But thereafter, you see what's happening now in Pakistan cricket, that there's a lot of

00:36:26.220 --> 00:36:27.220
[Guest]: talent coming through.

00:36:27.220 --> 00:36:28.220
[Guest]: There's a factory.

00:36:28.220 --> 00:36:30.220
[Guest]: Has this always been, I think.

00:36:30.220 --> 00:36:32.340
[Guest]: It has.

00:36:32.340 --> 00:36:37.380
[Guest]: Because they don't have a proper training, coaching system, a lot of this talent comes

00:36:37.380 --> 00:36:38.660
[Guest]: out raw.

00:36:38.660 --> 00:36:43.220
[Guest]: And because it's raw, in T20, everything that is a surprise is an advantage.

00:36:43.220 --> 00:36:47.780
[Guest]: So I'm not surprised they are the number one T20 team in the world.

00:36:47.780 --> 00:36:50.940
[Guest]: But what people don't realize is that two years later, there's a completely different

00:36:50.940 --> 00:36:53.020
[Guest]: set of people playing for Pakistan.

00:36:53.020 --> 00:36:55.700
[Guest]: And two years later, there's another completely different set of people playing for Pakistan.

00:36:55.700 --> 00:36:56.700
[Guest]: There are some survivors.

00:36:56.700 --> 00:37:00.580
[Guest]: Hafeez is a survivor and Shoaib Malik is a survivor.

00:37:00.580 --> 00:37:02.380
[Guest]: But otherwise, just look at the bowlers.

00:37:02.380 --> 00:37:04.020
[Guest]: Two years ago, who was bowling for Pakistan?

00:37:04.020 --> 00:37:07.820
[Guest]: Bahab Riaz, Mohammad Aamir, Mohammad Aamir is, they've lost, virtually lost Mohammad

00:37:07.820 --> 00:37:08.820
[Guest]: Aamir.

00:37:08.820 --> 00:37:14.140
[Guest]: So I think they needed, if they had the Dravid's and Tendulkar's and the Laxman's around them,

00:37:14.140 --> 00:37:16.180
[Guest]: then they would have been different.

00:37:16.180 --> 00:37:17.280
[Guest]: But that's their problem.

00:37:17.280 --> 00:37:20.740
[Amit Varma]: And would you say that the values that the Dravid and the Laxman and the Tendulkar epitomized

00:37:20.740 --> 00:37:21.740
[Guest]: are no longer there?

00:37:21.740 --> 00:37:22.740
[Guest]: Oh, no, I don't say that.

00:37:22.740 --> 00:37:27.700
[Guest]: I mean, I look at Ajinkya Rane, I look at Chhatteshwar Pujara and for all the outward

00:37:27.700 --> 00:37:33.380
[Guest]: appearance Virat Kohli retains a great love for the traditions of the game.

00:37:33.380 --> 00:37:38.820
[Guest]: Virat Kohli is in the way he bats, is as much a traditionalist as anybody else.

00:37:38.820 --> 00:37:43.260
[Guest]: And nobody can ever say that Virat Kohli doesn't love the game enough.

00:37:43.260 --> 00:37:45.380
[Guest]: So to that extent, it's all there.

00:37:45.380 --> 00:37:50.080
[Guest]: But these are, we're talking of the complete top deck.

00:37:50.080 --> 00:37:54.340
[Guest]: Do the younger players want to go through the turmoil of playing Test match credit?

00:37:54.340 --> 00:37:57.180
[Guest]: Do they want to feel the ball going past their nose?

00:37:57.180 --> 00:38:02.260
[Guest]: When the moment that happens in a T20 game, you're called one short ball for the over,

00:38:02.260 --> 00:38:04.940
[Guest]: thank you very much, you can't bowl it again or whatever.

00:38:04.940 --> 00:38:09.420
[Guest]: I think there'll be fewer and fewer people who now want to go through the rigor of playing

00:38:09.420 --> 00:38:10.860
[Guest]: Test match cricket.

00:38:10.860 --> 00:38:13.980
[Guest]: And if you're an Ishan Sharma, you're an Ajinkya Rane, where you've reached a certain level

00:38:13.980 --> 00:38:15.260
[Guest]: playing a certain game.

00:38:15.260 --> 00:38:18.700
[Guest]: The kid says, but yaar unko IPL contract milega kya?

00:38:18.700 --> 00:38:23.140
[Guest]: So I don't know if the next kid wants to be a Pujara or an Ishan Sharma, or he wants to

00:38:23.140 --> 00:38:25.820
[Guest]: be someone who will come with a peculiar action and bowl four overs.

00:38:25.820 --> 00:38:29.180
[Amit Varma]: In fact, it's interesting that when I spoke about the current generation, the two players

00:38:29.180 --> 00:38:32.620
[Amit Varma]: you named, I mean, Virat, of course, is exceptional, and we'll come to him later, but the two players

00:38:32.620 --> 00:38:37.140
[Amit Varma]: you named, Rahane and Pujara, almost seem anachronistic.

00:38:37.140 --> 00:38:40.980
[Amit Varma]: Also in the way they play their cricket, which we'll come to, which it doesn't seem to quite,

00:38:40.980 --> 00:38:44.140
[Amit Varma]: you know, they're not, they're almost sort of traditionalist players who would have been

00:38:44.140 --> 00:38:49.180
[Amit Varma]: great, maybe a generation earlier, but now you kind of wonder, do they really fit in?

00:38:49.180 --> 00:38:53.580
[Guest]: Pujara would probably have been far better off playing in an earlier era, right?

00:38:53.580 --> 00:38:57.220
[Guest]: Because he's now under pressure to deliver every time.

00:38:57.220 --> 00:39:02.140
[Guest]: I think we've made a couple of good players very insecure.

00:39:02.140 --> 00:39:06.740
[Guest]: The Pujaras and the Rahanes, and even to some extent, Ravi Chand and Ashwin.

00:39:06.740 --> 00:39:09.180
[Guest]: Ashwin is a Kumble incarnation.

00:39:09.180 --> 00:39:14.460
[Guest]: He's the same height, the similar education, love, similar intelligence, similar things.

00:39:14.460 --> 00:39:18.620
[Guest]: And just as Kumble was told all his life that you don't turn a ball and he took 600 wickets.

00:39:18.620 --> 00:39:24.620
[Guest]: Ashwin, we're always searching for what Ashwin cannot do when he's got 330 test wickets.

00:39:24.620 --> 00:39:27.380
[Guest]: And yet we are finding reasons to keep leaving Ashwin out.

00:39:27.380 --> 00:39:30.100
[Guest]: And I mean, we go across the world and they laugh at us.

00:39:30.100 --> 00:39:35.660
[Guest]: He's got 330 wickets, he's got to 300 faster than anybody in the history of the game.

00:39:35.660 --> 00:39:38.220
[Guest]: And we say, yeah, that's because he bowled in those conditions.

00:39:38.220 --> 00:39:40.340
[Guest]: Jimmy Anderson's just come to Sri Lanka.

00:39:40.340 --> 00:39:42.260
[Guest]: He's played two test matches, got one wicket.

00:39:42.260 --> 00:39:45.700
[Guest]: And he says he feels like a fish out of water, he's not playing the next test match.

00:39:45.700 --> 00:39:49.980
[Guest]: And here's a spinner who's, I mean, Kumble took three, four turns to learn to bowl overseas.

00:39:49.980 --> 00:39:54.980
[Guest]: Yeah, but anyway, to come back to the point that these three people are classic old fashioned

00:39:54.980 --> 00:39:55.980
[Guest]: players.

00:39:55.980 --> 00:39:58.540
[Guest]: It's interesting where they come from.

00:39:58.540 --> 00:40:00.780
[Guest]: Rane comes from middle class Mumbai.

00:40:00.780 --> 00:40:04.420
[Guest]: Pujara comes from a father who was so much in love with the way cricket was played that

00:40:04.420 --> 00:40:06.300
[Guest]: he made him that kind of player.

00:40:06.300 --> 00:40:12.300
[Amit Varma]: And Ashwin comes from, I don't think he comes from Chennai, I think he comes from Madras.

00:40:12.300 --> 00:40:13.300
[Amit Varma]: That's very well said.

00:40:13.300 --> 00:40:16.460
[Amit Varma]: Do you think Ashwin should be in the one day side?

00:40:16.460 --> 00:40:20.700
[Guest]: It depends on his, I think it's his fielding that's letting him down.

00:40:20.700 --> 00:40:26.860
[Guest]: Because today, in the way Virat Kohli wants to construct a side, he wants the 15 runs,

00:40:26.860 --> 00:40:29.540
[Guest]: the 10 runs that Jadeja will save for him in the field.

00:40:29.540 --> 00:40:36.380
[Guest]: And Jadeja is, I mean, I think his, Yuvraaj at his peak, is that standard as a fielder.

00:40:36.380 --> 00:40:41.700
[Guest]: So the moment Ashwin is a little slow chasing the ball to third man, you start to think,

00:40:41.700 --> 00:40:45.560
[Guest]: oops, that's another single gone there, that's another two runs gone there.

00:40:45.560 --> 00:40:50.380
[Guest]: But I would definitely have him because at number seven, you still want someone who can

00:40:50.380 --> 00:40:51.380
[Guest]: bat.

00:40:51.380 --> 00:40:52.900
[Guest]: We hardly have people who can bat and bowl.

00:40:52.900 --> 00:40:54.180
[Guest]: I would definitely have him in the mix.

00:40:54.180 --> 00:40:56.700
[Guest]: Ashwin Jadeja and the two wrist spinners and Krunal Pandya.

00:40:56.700 --> 00:40:57.700
[Guest]: This would be my five.

