[Guest]: playing into his hands.

00:43:39.860 --> 00:43:44.140
[Guest]: The same wrist spinners cannot buy a wicket in Test match cricket.

00:43:44.140 --> 00:43:46.900
[Guest]: Kuldeep Yadav is not yet a Test match cricketer.

00:43:46.900 --> 00:43:49.340
[Guest]: Chahal has not even been considered for Test match cricket.

00:43:49.340 --> 00:43:51.660
[Guest]: Imran Tahir is not a Test match cricketer.

00:43:51.660 --> 00:43:57.380
[Guest]: Rashid Khan, the world's number one T20 player, couldn't bowl a spell right in the Test match.

00:43:57.380 --> 00:43:59.060
[Guest]: Sunil Narayan is not a Test match cricketer.

00:43:59.060 --> 00:44:03.420
[Guest]: You look at all these spinners that are doing well, they don't do well in Test match cricket

00:44:03.420 --> 00:44:06.460
[Guest]: because batsmen are not charging and hitting them through the line.

00:44:06.460 --> 00:44:09.980
[Guest]: But they're waiting and milking them for a single.

00:44:09.980 --> 00:44:12.460
[Guest]: And all of a sudden, they don't have the guile to get them out.

00:44:12.460 --> 00:44:15.780
[Guest]: So that's a change that T20 has happened.

00:44:15.780 --> 00:44:18.180
[Guest]: It's brought about bowlers who are very good when they're attacked.

00:44:18.180 --> 00:44:21.380
[Guest]: And the batsmen have no choice but to attack because the run rate is hovering over his

00:44:21.380 --> 00:44:22.380
[Amit Varma]: head.

00:44:22.380 --> 00:44:23.380
[Amit Varma]: That's the grammar of the game.

00:44:23.380 --> 00:44:27.260
[Amit Varma]: And that also buttresses the point that T20 and Test cricket, you know, calling them both

00:44:27.260 --> 00:44:30.820
[Amit Varma]: cricket sort of implies they are the same sport and they're not the same sport.

00:44:30.820 --> 00:44:34.180
[Amit Varma]: They're different sports with different imperatives and different demands.

00:44:34.180 --> 00:44:37.580
[Amit Varma]: And I would not even say one is necessarily superior to the other.

00:44:37.580 --> 00:44:41.420
[Amit Varma]: That's a question of taste and nostalgia and those play into it.

00:44:41.420 --> 00:44:45.780
[Amit Varma]: But you know, the argument I made when I spoke about why Test cricket might be dying is that

00:44:45.780 --> 00:44:49.580
[Amit Varma]: because T20 is so much more lucrative for young people coming into the game, because

00:44:49.580 --> 00:44:53.740
[Amit Varma]: there's a much better chance of grabbing an IPL contract and making a lot of money that

00:44:53.740 --> 00:44:57.220
[Amit Varma]: way rather than actually play for Test cricket for India.

00:44:57.220 --> 00:45:02.140
[Amit Varma]: You know, young cricketers are incentivized to tailor their skills towards T20 cricket,

00:45:02.140 --> 00:45:05.900
[Amit Varma]: which is why you might end up with a generation which cannot play swing bowling anymore, as

00:45:05.900 --> 00:45:06.900
[Amit Varma]: you pointed out.

00:45:06.900 --> 00:45:11.140
[Amit Varma]: And we might never, for example, have a good Test series in England because those skills

00:45:11.140 --> 00:45:12.140
[Amit Varma]: are simply gone.

00:45:12.140 --> 00:45:13.700
[Guest]: Is that a worry you share?

00:45:13.700 --> 00:45:15.140
[Guest]: There's another reason.

00:45:15.140 --> 00:45:19.740
[Guest]: Just imagine now that you're a television network that is keeping our game alive by

00:45:19.740 --> 00:45:23.380
[Guest]: the vast amounts of money you're pumping into the game.

00:45:23.380 --> 00:45:26.260
[Guest]: And you're paying what 40-50 crores a day, suppose.

00:45:26.260 --> 00:45:27.260
[Guest]: I think it's more than that.

00:45:27.260 --> 00:45:30.620
[Guest]: But whatever, let's assume it's 40-50 crores a day.

00:45:30.620 --> 00:45:33.340
[Guest]: And there's India versus West Indies.

00:45:33.340 --> 00:45:36.140
[Guest]: They're not allowed to play the fourth day.

00:45:36.140 --> 00:45:39.820
[Guest]: So suddenly fourth day gone, fifth day gone, but your contract requires you to pay that

00:45:39.820 --> 00:45:40.820
[Guest]: money, right?

00:45:40.820 --> 00:45:44.300
[Guest]: So straight away, your 200 crores has gone to charity.

00:45:44.300 --> 00:45:47.540
[Guest]: Why would you want to put so much money in Test match cricket?

00:45:47.540 --> 00:45:51.260
[Guest]: A lot of people say they're watching Test match cricket and they say Test match cricket

00:45:51.260 --> 00:45:53.820
[Guest]: is the ultimate and Test match cricket is the greatest.

00:45:53.820 --> 00:45:56.380
[Guest]: Yeah, Mother Teresa was too.

00:45:56.380 --> 00:45:58.740
[Guest]: These are all Mother Teresa statements.

00:45:58.740 --> 00:46:02.260
[Guest]: If you are that interested in the game, then you buy a ticket and go and watch the game.

00:46:02.260 --> 00:46:05.140
[Guest]: If you're that interested in the game, you sit in front of your television, boost the

00:46:05.140 --> 00:46:09.840
[Guest]: viewership figures and get people to advertise on it and be part of the cricket economy.

00:46:09.840 --> 00:46:13.700
[Guest]: If you're merely following scores on Crickbuzz, you're not contributing to the Test match

00:46:13.700 --> 00:46:14.700
[Guest]: cricket economy.

00:46:14.700 --> 00:46:19.120
[Guest]: You're still saying, I like Test cricket, but you're doing nothing for its sustenance.

00:46:19.120 --> 00:46:25.260
[Guest]: It's like saying, I like poverty alleviation, but now I'll go and have a gin and tonic.

00:46:25.260 --> 00:46:29.980
[Guest]: So you've got to actually actively participate in that and that's not happening.

00:46:29.980 --> 00:46:31.540
[Guest]: So Test cricket will survive.

00:46:31.540 --> 00:46:33.180
[Guest]: I'm not saying Test cricket will die.

00:46:33.180 --> 00:46:37.060
[Guest]: Test cricket will survive because it's got too much going for it.

00:46:37.060 --> 00:46:40.020
[Guest]: You'll never otherwise get 50 days of live cricket on a telecast.

00:46:40.020 --> 00:46:41.980
[Guest]: Telecast needs dal chawal as well.

00:46:41.980 --> 00:46:44.580
[Guest]: So that is Test cricket.

00:46:44.580 --> 00:46:48.820
[Guest]: And even now there is a Kohli generation that says we love Test match cricket, that wants

00:46:48.820 --> 00:46:50.620
[Guest]: to do well in Test match cricket.

00:46:50.620 --> 00:46:55.860
[Guest]: The records go back 140 years and you can compare over 140 years.

00:46:55.860 --> 00:47:00.420
[Guest]: T20 is like the 17th premiership game.

00:47:00.420 --> 00:47:04.100
[Guest]: Do you remember what happened between Arsenal and Southampton?

00:47:04.100 --> 00:47:06.700
[Guest]: Do you remember what happened between North East United and Mumbai AFC?

00:47:06.700 --> 00:47:07.700
[Guest]: No, I don't.

00:47:07.700 --> 00:47:08.880
[Guest]: T20 cricket is like that.

00:47:08.880 --> 00:47:11.380
[Guest]: You come there, have your fun and you go back.

00:47:11.380 --> 00:47:14.500
[Guest]: There's no place for a T20 game in history.

00:47:14.500 --> 00:47:15.500
[Guest]: It's like Major League Baseball.

00:47:15.500 --> 00:47:17.560
[Guest]: Do you know what happened in the 42nd game?

00:47:17.560 --> 00:47:18.560
[Guest]: You don't know.

00:47:18.560 --> 00:47:22.180
[Guest]: So records are maintained over a period of time.

00:47:22.180 --> 00:47:26.260
[Guest]: And so a particular performance gets forgotten very quickly.

00:47:26.260 --> 00:47:28.740
[Guest]: So that is why I think Test cricket will survive.

00:47:28.740 --> 00:47:34.460
[Guest]: The reason I want Test cricket to never die is because Test cricket is the greatest manifestation

00:47:34.460 --> 00:47:36.300
[Guest]: of life on a sporting field.

00:47:36.300 --> 00:47:40.780
[Guest]: You get a second chance, you grind your way out of trouble.

00:47:40.780 --> 00:47:44.340
[Guest]: We all go through situations in life where we think the world is against us.

00:47:44.340 --> 00:47:47.700
[Guest]: That's two fast bowlers bowling at you on a green track.

00:47:47.700 --> 00:47:49.540
[Guest]: But you don't give your wicket away.

00:47:49.540 --> 00:47:51.260
[Guest]: You hang in and you hang in and you hang in.

00:47:51.260 --> 00:47:54.420
[Guest]: And then when the other bowler comes, you squeeze a single here and squeeze a single

00:47:54.420 --> 00:47:55.420
[Guest]: there.

00:47:55.420 --> 00:47:56.420
[Guest]: That is what we do in life.

00:47:56.420 --> 00:47:57.760
[Guest]: And we're going through a difficult phase.

00:47:57.760 --> 00:47:59.800
[Guest]: So I hope Test cricket never goes.

00:47:59.800 --> 00:48:04.560
[Guest]: But I think Test cricket will become what marketing people call the loss leader.

00:48:04.560 --> 00:48:05.900
[Guest]: It will continue to make losses.

00:48:05.900 --> 00:48:07.460
[Guest]: It will be funded by T20.

00:48:07.460 --> 00:48:08.460
[Guest]: Does it make losses?

00:48:08.460 --> 00:48:09.460
[Guest]: Oh, 100%.

00:48:09.460 --> 00:48:10.460
[Guest]: 100% it does.

00:48:10.460 --> 00:48:13.120
[Guest]: I mean, you'll find people say, no, it doesn't make losses.

00:48:13.120 --> 00:48:14.120
[Guest]: Of course it does.

00:48:14.120 --> 00:48:18.660
[Guest]: I mean, you must ask people who put money behind sport.

00:48:18.660 --> 00:48:22.620
[Guest]: My sort of dipstick is media buyers.

00:48:22.620 --> 00:48:26.320
[Guest]: I think media buyers understand the market better than anybody else because they're spending

00:48:26.320 --> 00:48:27.320
[Guest]: someone else's money.

00:48:27.320 --> 00:48:28.700
[Guest]: They have skin in the game.

00:48:28.700 --> 00:48:35.460
[Guest]: If you ask them, bid for Test cricket alone, ask them what percentage of the bid they would

00:48:35.460 --> 00:48:39.260
[Guest]: put in, if they would put in a bid at all.

00:48:39.260 --> 00:48:40.740
[Guest]: You'll get some very interesting answers.

00:48:40.740 --> 00:48:45.260
[Guest]: I've asked that question, but I've got those answers in confidence.

00:48:45.260 --> 00:48:51.860
[Guest]: But it'll be very interesting to ask people that this massive billion dollar television

00:48:51.860 --> 00:48:56.380
[Guest]: contracts, if you had to bid separately for Test match cricket, how much would you bid?

00:48:56.380 --> 00:48:58.180
[Guest]: What percentage, if at all?

00:48:58.180 --> 00:48:59.180
[Amit Varma]: Right.

00:48:59.180 --> 00:49:03.080
[Amit Varma]: And, you know, like you, I love Test cricket and you put it so beautifully, manifestation

00:49:03.080 --> 00:49:04.180
[Amit Varma]: of life on a cricket field.

00:49:04.180 --> 00:49:08.580
[Amit Varma]: I think it reveals character like no other sport can and no other form of cricket, which

00:49:08.580 --> 00:49:10.700
[Amit Varma]: are different sports anyway.

00:49:10.700 --> 00:49:15.060
[Amit Varma]: And like you, I hope it survives and continues to be subsidized by T20 cricket, as is no

00:49:15.060 --> 00:49:16.620
[Amit Varma]: doubt the case.

00:49:16.620 --> 00:49:21.560
[Amit Varma]: But a lot of people who express these sentiments also are just to use that popular phrase these

00:49:21.560 --> 00:49:23.140
[Amit Varma]: days, virtue signaling.

00:49:23.140 --> 00:49:24.860
[Guest]: They're not actually putting their money where their mouth is.

00:49:24.860 --> 00:49:26.620
[Guest]: They're like the Manchester United fans.

00:49:26.620 --> 00:49:29.820
[Guest]: I don't actually I don't know anything about English football, but my club is Manchester

00:49:29.820 --> 00:49:30.820
[Unknown]: United.

00:49:30.820 --> 00:49:31.820
[Guest]: They're a hardcore United supporters.

00:49:31.820 --> 00:49:35.780
[Guest]: But if I don't know anything about Premiership, I'm United, you know, it's like that.

00:49:35.780 --> 00:49:40.860
[Guest]: A lot of people who have no idea about the glory, about all the elements of Test match

00:49:40.860 --> 00:49:43.020
[Guest]: cricket will tell you, I love Test match cricket.

00:49:43.020 --> 00:49:44.220
[Guest]: It's pure cricket.

00:49:44.220 --> 00:49:49.100
[Guest]: As if to say that T20 cricket is full of chemicals and preservatives that are going to kill you

00:49:49.100 --> 00:49:50.100
[Guest]: the moment you hit it.

00:49:50.100 --> 00:49:55.460
[Guest]: No, T20 cricket is extraordinarily skilled cricket, extraordinary skills.

00:49:55.460 --> 00:49:58.940
[Guest]: You ask someone to score 12 in three balls to win a game.

00:49:58.940 --> 00:50:00.320
[Guest]: You have to have skills.

00:50:00.320 --> 00:50:01.540
[Guest]: You have to have presence of mind.

00:50:01.540 --> 00:50:03.000
[Guest]: You have to be calm.

00:50:03.000 --> 00:50:04.900
[Guest]: You have to be there to be able to win it.

00:50:04.900 --> 00:50:06.900
[Guest]: You've got to know one mistake and I'm gone.

00:50:06.900 --> 00:50:09.020
[Guest]: It just requires a completely different set of skills.

00:50:09.020 --> 00:50:10.020
[Amit Varma]: Right.

00:50:10.020 --> 00:50:14.260
[Amit Varma]: It's not that one set of skills is necessarily superior or inferior to the other skills.

00:50:14.260 --> 00:50:17.220
[Amit Varma]: They're just different skills and time becomes a great element.

00:50:17.220 --> 00:50:20.620
[Amit Varma]: Time becomes a great restraint and a great challenge in the shorter forms of the game.

00:50:20.620 --> 00:50:24.060
[Amit Varma]: And therefore, you have to develop skills according to that.

00:50:24.060 --> 00:50:26.840
[Amit Varma]: And the interesting thing is you pointed out how Kohli still loves Test cricket.

00:50:26.840 --> 00:50:31.140
[Amit Varma]: But one reason for that could be that Kohli sort of grew up as a kid in the generation

00:50:31.140 --> 00:50:35.460
[Amit Varma]: which held Tendulkar and Dravid and all these guys on awe and he got some of those values.

00:50:35.460 --> 00:50:40.380
[Amit Varma]: But I mean, I don't know any of the kids today personally, but we'll say Hardik Pandya and

00:50:40.380 --> 00:50:43.100
[Amit Varma]: so on still revere Test cricket in that way.

00:50:43.100 --> 00:50:45.660
[Amit Varma]: They might pay lip service to it because they've seen the captain do it.

00:50:45.660 --> 00:50:47.060
[Guest]: They will say that.

00:50:47.060 --> 00:50:52.700
[Guest]: I have this fantasy world I want to reside in once where a truth serum exists.

00:50:52.700 --> 00:50:57.740
[Guest]: Where every time I see someone, I just creep up from behind and jab a truth serum into

00:50:57.740 --> 00:50:59.060
[Guest]: them and now they have to tell the truth.

00:50:59.060 --> 00:51:00.780
[Guest]: Wasn't there a Jim Carrey movie like that?

00:51:00.780 --> 00:51:01.780
[Guest]: I don't remember.

00:51:01.780 --> 00:51:06.300
[Guest]: And then I'd love to hear what people have to say about Test match cricket to see whether

00:51:06.300 --> 00:51:09.340
[Guest]: they actually want to enjoy it the same way or not.

00:51:09.340 --> 00:51:10.500
[Guest]: They call it dumbing down.

00:51:10.500 --> 00:51:11.980
[Guest]: Yes, it is.

00:51:11.980 --> 00:51:15.300
[Guest]: It's dumbing down by your definition of what you should be.

00:51:15.300 --> 00:51:17.380
[Guest]: It is because it's our intellectual level.

00:51:17.380 --> 00:51:23.540
[Unknown]: It's not kids, you know, you know, it's not the kind of poetry we studied when we were

00:51:23.540 --> 00:51:24.540
[Unknown]: children.

00:51:24.540 --> 00:51:25.540
[Guest]: Look at Chetan Bhagat.

00:51:25.540 --> 00:51:26.540
[Guest]: Look at.

00:51:26.540 --> 00:51:27.780
[Guest]: He sells, he sells books.

00:51:27.780 --> 00:51:29.420
[Guest]: He's writing to a different audience.

00:51:29.420 --> 00:51:31.460
[Guest]: Someone else writes to a different audience.

00:51:31.460 --> 00:51:33.980
[Guest]: There is a Satyajit Ray movie.

00:51:33.980 --> 00:51:35.420
[Guest]: There was a Manmohan Desai movie.

00:51:35.420 --> 00:51:37.060
[Guest]: So you choose what you get.

00:51:37.060 --> 00:51:38.620
[Amit Varma]: You pick what you want.

00:51:38.620 --> 00:51:40.180
[Amit Varma]: And it's not even the same kind of difference.

00:51:40.180 --> 00:51:44.100
[Amit Varma]: I mean, it's the anchoring effect that we're used to cricket being over five days.

00:51:44.100 --> 00:51:48.220
[Amit Varma]: You know, if a Test cricket did not exist and T20s were the dominant form of the game

00:51:48.220 --> 00:51:50.500
[Amit Varma]: and then somebody said, hey, I have a brainwave.

00:51:50.500 --> 00:51:52.460
[Amit Varma]: Let's play this over five days.

00:51:52.460 --> 00:51:55.540
[Amit Varma]: You'd laugh him out of the room the same way if someone said that a football match should

00:51:55.540 --> 00:51:56.660
[Amit Varma]: not be 90 minutes.

00:51:56.660 --> 00:51:58.460
[Amit Varma]: Let's have a six hour game.

00:51:58.460 --> 00:52:01.740
[Amit Varma]: You'd laugh him out of the room and the skills required for that would be completely different.

00:52:01.740 --> 00:52:05.060
[Amit Varma]: But they wouldn't necessarily be romanticized over this one.

00:52:05.060 --> 00:52:08.380
[Guest]: You know, you said something is, is it, is it really cricket as we knew it?

00:52:08.380 --> 00:52:10.260
[Guest]: The laws are largely the same.

00:52:10.260 --> 00:52:13.060
[Guest]: There are little playing conditions here and there that are different.

00:52:13.060 --> 00:52:16.140
[Guest]: Like football spawned futsal.

00:52:16.140 --> 00:52:18.660
[Guest]: Should we call cricket, quicket?

00:52:18.660 --> 00:52:20.060
[Guest]: And say, okay, that was cricket.

00:52:20.060 --> 00:52:21.060
[Guest]: This is quicket.

00:52:21.060 --> 00:52:23.180
[Guest]: You know, let's, let's play.

00:52:23.180 --> 00:52:24.260
[Guest]: Let's play this.

00:52:24.260 --> 00:52:31.180
[Guest]: But eventually, you know, the, the romantics always have to bow to the, to commerce.

00:52:31.180 --> 00:52:36.540
[Guest]: Whether you're a broadcaster, wants to radio and moves to television or whether you want

00:52:36.540 --> 00:52:38.540
[Guest]: to play, you want to play limited overs cricket.

00:52:38.540 --> 00:52:39.900
[Guest]: I mean, there's, there's just no comparison.

00:52:39.900 --> 00:52:42.500
[Guest]: Look what AB de Villiers has done.

00:52:42.500 --> 00:52:43.500
[Amit Varma]: Mind-blowing.

00:52:43.500 --> 00:52:44.500
[Amit Varma]: What do you think of AB de Villiers?

00:52:44.500 --> 00:52:45.500
[Amit Varma]: He's a genius.

00:52:45.500 --> 00:52:48.380
[Amit Varma]: I mean, I used to say at one point that partly because of the imperatives of the new kind

00:52:48.380 --> 00:52:52.700
[Amit Varma]: of cricket that he is more skilled than any other player, batsman in the history of the

00:52:52.700 --> 00:52:55.340
[Amit Varma]: game because of the 360 degree game.

00:52:55.340 --> 00:52:59.740
[Guest]: I'm just a bit worried about that because we have seen certain set of people.

00:52:59.740 --> 00:53:01.980
[Guest]: We have not seen, say, Lara in his prime.

00:53:01.980 --> 00:53:04.940
[Guest]: There was not that much television or even going further back.

00:53:04.940 --> 00:53:10.820
[Guest]: So if we consign that, if we confine it to the period under our observation, he's just

00:53:10.820 --> 00:53:11.820
[Guest]: a genius.

00:53:11.820 --> 00:53:16.780
[Guest]: The things he does on a cricket ground that should be outlawed, that should not be allowed.

00:53:16.780 --> 00:53:19.180
[Guest]: And the other day he had a switch at six over mid wicket.

00:53:19.180 --> 00:53:20.180
[Guest]: Wow.

00:53:20.180 --> 00:53:21.900
[Guest]: I mean, I, I admire the switch.

00:53:21.900 --> 00:53:25.500
[Guest]: I think it should never have a place in cricket because it's so against the bowler, but he

00:53:25.500 --> 00:53:26.780
[Guest]: can hit a switch at six.

00:53:26.780 --> 00:53:29.660
[Guest]: He can lap a six over, over a fine leg.

00:53:29.660 --> 00:53:31.340
[Guest]: He can reverse lap it over third man.

00:53:31.340 --> 00:53:33.260
[Guest]: And he's doing that to Dale Steyn.

00:53:33.260 --> 00:53:36.380
[Guest]: He's hitting a hundred of 31 balls, Samit.

00:53:36.380 --> 00:53:37.380
[Guest]: Hundred of 31 balls.

00:53:37.380 --> 00:53:39.900
[Guest]: I told someone the other day, I said, you know, I used to be playing book cricket and

00:53:39.900 --> 00:53:42.940
[Amit Varma]: I didn't even score a hundred and thirty one balls in book cricket.

00:53:42.940 --> 00:53:44.380
[Amit Varma]: I used to play book cricket as well.

00:53:44.380 --> 00:53:45.380
[Amit Varma]: Who remembers book cricket?

00:53:45.380 --> 00:53:46.380
[Amit Varma]: Outrageous.

00:53:46.380 --> 00:53:48.480
[Guest]: That talent is just outrageous.

00:53:48.480 --> 00:53:52.820
[Guest]: And then he plays 240 balls to score 25 or 30.

00:53:52.820 --> 00:53:53.820
[Guest]: Because that's what the game demanded.

00:53:53.820 --> 00:53:54.820
[Guest]: And he can do that too.

00:53:54.820 --> 00:53:55.820
[Unknown]: And he can do that too.

00:53:55.820 --> 00:53:56.820
[Unknown]: What a player.

00:53:56.820 --> 00:53:57.820
[Unknown]: Amazing.

00:53:57.820 --> 00:53:58.820
[Amit Varma]: What a player.

00:53:58.820 --> 00:54:04.220
[Amit Varma]: And also another amazing player, Virat Kohli, where he'll have a similar impact, but without

00:54:04.220 --> 00:54:08.100
[Amit Varma]: all these switch hits, just playing the orthodox game to a different purpose.

00:54:08.100 --> 00:54:12.500
[Guest]: 2016 or the 2017, the IPL just come and go so quickly.

00:54:12.500 --> 00:54:15.700
[Guest]: He almost got a thousand runs in the IPL.

00:54:15.700 --> 00:54:19.740
[Amit Varma]: I think he got about 974, the same as Bradman series record.

00:54:19.740 --> 00:54:24.300
[Guest]: No switch hit, no lap shots, just proper correct cricket shots.

00:54:24.300 --> 00:54:29.760
[Guest]: In the last three years, the evolution of Virat Kohli has been as thrilling to watch

00:54:29.760 --> 00:54:33.160
[Guest]: as the evolution of any great player in the history of the game.

00:54:33.160 --> 00:54:37.260
[Guest]: And I just thought the way he played in England earlier this year, he was lucky.

00:54:37.260 --> 00:54:38.260
[Guest]: Everybody is lucky.

00:54:38.260 --> 00:54:39.260
[Guest]: Tendulkar was lucky.

00:54:39.260 --> 00:54:40.260
[Guest]: Dravid was lucky.

00:54:40.260 --> 00:54:41.260
[Guest]: Sobers was lucky.

00:54:41.260 --> 00:54:42.260
[Guest]: Bradman was lucky.

00:54:42.260 --> 00:54:43.260
[Guest]: You make your own luck, as I say.

00:54:43.260 --> 00:54:48.860
[Guest]: I mean, on 20, playing and missing against Anderson, he gets dropped by David Malan.

00:54:48.860 --> 00:54:49.940
[Guest]: And then he goes and scores 100.

00:54:49.940 --> 00:54:52.780
[Guest]: He made 530 runs in that series.

00:54:52.780 --> 00:54:56.260
[Guest]: The last time he went there, he'd be at 140.

00:54:56.260 --> 00:54:59.460
[Guest]: And the way he played Anderson, he just said, I will not get out to Anderson.

00:54:59.460 --> 00:55:00.660
[Guest]: He played and missed, yes.

00:55:00.660 --> 00:55:03.100
[Guest]: But he could just see the ferocious desire.

00:55:03.100 --> 00:55:09.180
[Guest]: To me, Kohli versus Anderson this year was like a sermon being delivered on the greatness

00:55:09.180 --> 00:55:11.140
[Guest]: of Test match cricket.

00:55:11.140 --> 00:55:14.620
[Guest]: Because Anderson could not be taken off after two overs.

00:55:14.620 --> 00:55:17.580
[Guest]: You could not suddenly say, but I can't have more than one slip.

00:55:17.580 --> 00:55:19.980
[Guest]: I must have five fielders outside the circle.

00:55:19.980 --> 00:55:22.020
[Guest]: No, no prisoners taken.

00:55:22.020 --> 00:55:23.180
[Guest]: No chance.

00:55:23.180 --> 00:55:26.140
[Guest]: He's not going anywhere for the next nine overs.

00:55:26.140 --> 00:55:28.100
[Guest]: You've got 54 balls coming at you.

00:55:28.100 --> 00:55:29.540
[Guest]: You better play them.

00:55:29.540 --> 00:55:30.980
[Guest]: And I can have six around the bat.

00:55:30.980 --> 00:55:31.980
[Guest]: I can have seven.

00:55:31.980 --> 00:55:33.300
[Guest]: I can do what I want.

00:55:33.300 --> 00:55:35.180
[Guest]: Now every ball is an exam.

00:55:35.180 --> 00:55:36.860
[Guest]: You didn't like thermodynamics, right?

00:55:36.860 --> 00:55:40.620
[Guest]: You've got 54 thermodynamics papers coming at you one after the other.

00:55:40.620 --> 00:55:46.060
[Guest]: But to me, I mean, I would watch Anderson and you know, in England, if you leave a ball

00:55:46.060 --> 00:55:51.060
[Guest]: that you meant to play and you just leave it, those crowds out there will go, well left

00:55:51.060 --> 00:55:52.060
[Guest]: young man.

00:55:52.060 --> 00:55:53.060
[Guest]: Because they'll get it.

00:55:53.060 --> 00:55:54.060
[Guest]: Well left young man.

00:55:54.060 --> 00:55:55.060
[Guest]: Yeah.

00:55:55.060 --> 00:55:57.540
[Guest]: If you want to enjoy Test cricket, go to the Boxing Day Test.

00:55:57.540 --> 00:55:59.620
[Guest]: But that's in Melbourne where you're one of 90,000.

00:55:59.620 --> 00:56:00.620
[Guest]: You're an ant.

00:56:00.620 --> 00:56:02.740
[Guest]: Go to England and watch Test match cricket.

00:56:02.740 --> 00:56:03.740
[Guest]: They'll clap.

00:56:03.740 --> 00:56:04.740
[Guest]: They clap everybody.

00:56:04.740 --> 00:56:07.700
[Guest]: In our country, we're reaching a stage we're not allowed to clap for the opposition.

00:56:07.700 --> 00:56:12.780
[Amit Varma]: So tell me something, 10 years ago, 11 years ago, when Kohli kind of first started appearing

00:56:12.780 --> 00:56:17.860
[Amit Varma]: on the scene when he got, you know, when he came out of the under 19 ranks and he was

00:56:17.860 --> 00:56:19.980
[Amit Varma]: sort of promoted up to the senior ranks.

00:56:19.980 --> 00:56:21.460
[Amit Varma]: With a temper and a tattoo.

00:56:21.460 --> 00:56:24.380
[Guest]: Did you have a sense that he will become this?

00:56:24.380 --> 00:56:25.380
[Amit Varma]: No.

00:56:25.380 --> 00:56:28.180
[Guest]: I mean, it's very easy to say I spotted that talent.

00:56:28.180 --> 00:56:29.180
[Guest]: Hindsight bias.

00:56:29.180 --> 00:56:30.180
[Guest]: Nobody did.

00:56:30.180 --> 00:56:31.180
[Guest]: Nobody did.

00:56:31.180 --> 00:56:32.180
[Guest]: Nobody did.

00:56:32.180 --> 00:56:33.820
[Guest]: In fact, we still said the moving ball as late as 2014.

00:56:33.820 --> 00:56:35.540
[Guest]: We were saying, wow, what a player.

00:56:35.540 --> 00:56:36.540
[Guest]: But you know what?

00:56:36.540 --> 00:56:39.740
[Guest]: The moving ball troubles him.

00:56:39.740 --> 00:56:44.780
[Guest]: And I think it's come about, you see Kohli and you see arrogance.

00:56:44.780 --> 00:56:47.260
[Guest]: And you see Kohli and you think my way or the highway.

00:56:47.260 --> 00:56:51.180
[Guest]: You see Kohli and you think I want this, this, this, this is how it should be played.

00:56:51.180 --> 00:56:56.740
[Guest]: What you do not see is the extraordinary discipline that has taken him where he has reached.

00:56:56.740 --> 00:56:59.340
[Guest]: And that has not changed in the game over the last hundred years.

00:56:59.340 --> 00:57:04.700
[Guest]: Just knowing what is right for you, having the great perseverance to actually go and

00:57:04.700 --> 00:57:11.540
[Guest]: do that, nobody becomes great in test match cricket without having worked backside off.

00:57:11.540 --> 00:57:14.500
[Amit Varma]: And there is a sense, a stereotype that, oh, he's a very aggressive guy.

00:57:14.500 --> 00:57:18.500
[Amit Varma]: But I think what people don't realize is that the aggression is not just in the MCBC

00:57:18.500 --> 00:57:20.940
[Amit Varma]: gullies on the field or that kind of behavior.

00:57:20.940 --> 00:57:25.660
[Amit Varma]: That aggression is something that goes into his work ethic and that produces that intense

00:57:25.660 --> 00:57:30.740
[Amit Varma]: hunger, which is, I mean, I think he probably has the greatest work ethic of any sportsperson

00:57:30.740 --> 00:57:31.740
[Amit Varma]: I can remember.

00:57:31.740 --> 00:57:37.820
[Amit Varma]: I mean, I can't remember a fitter Indian cricket and you know, to turn himself from that teenager

00:57:37.820 --> 00:57:38.820
[Guest]: who we remember.

00:57:38.820 --> 00:57:43.220
[Guest]: Yeah, but you see, but you see, he also had outstanding fitness trainers.

00:57:43.220 --> 00:57:44.220
[Guest]: Right.

00:57:44.220 --> 00:57:46.660
[Guest]: He also had great dietitians.

00:57:46.660 --> 00:57:51.220
[Guest]: I have seen Rahul Dravid in a gym lifting weights and Rahul Dravid was putting his body

00:57:51.220 --> 00:57:55.540
[Guest]: through his body was complaining and screaming in 12 different languages.

00:57:55.540 --> 00:57:56.660
[Guest]: But he was still doing it.

00:57:56.660 --> 00:58:00.780
[Guest]: And when I was walking on the treadmill next door and I said to him after I said, Rahul,

00:58:00.780 --> 00:58:02.140
[Guest]: why are you doing all this?

00:58:02.140 --> 00:58:03.940
[Guest]: He said, I'm well over 30 now.

00:58:03.940 --> 00:58:06.060
[Guest]: I've got to be fitter than the next guy to survive.

00:58:06.060 --> 00:58:10.460
[Guest]: Rahul Dravid's work ethic, Tendulkar's work ethic was just unbelievable.

00:58:10.460 --> 00:58:15.180
[Guest]: What we are seeing with Kohli now is the chiseling of ability.

00:58:15.180 --> 00:58:18.340
[Guest]: But he's got he's got the best tools that an earlier generation did not have.

00:58:18.340 --> 00:58:20.100
[Guest]: He's got the technology, those guys really.

00:58:20.100 --> 00:58:21.100
[Guest]: He does.

00:58:21.100 --> 00:58:22.220
[Guest]: But the aggression does spill over as well.

00:58:22.220 --> 00:58:24.340
[Guest]: It's not only in it does spill over.

00:58:24.340 --> 00:58:29.180
[Amit Varma]: So when you kind of look back over this journey, like you, you started well before these inflection

00:58:29.180 --> 00:58:32.780
[Amit Varma]: points, you really started reporting at a time where you still had potbelly cricketers

00:58:32.780 --> 00:58:34.140
[Amit Varma]: on the field sometimes.

00:58:34.140 --> 00:58:39.420
[Amit Varma]: And there was a whole different sort of pace of playing and media meant something completely

00:58:39.420 --> 00:58:40.860
[Amit Varma]: different and all of that.

00:58:40.860 --> 00:58:44.660
[Amit Varma]: And you've sort of traveled all this distance and you look at the cricketers today.

00:58:44.660 --> 00:58:46.780
[Amit Varma]: And is it really the same game?

00:58:46.780 --> 00:58:49.500
[Amit Varma]: Other things you loved about cricket still there?

00:58:49.500 --> 00:58:50.500
[Amit Varma]: Have they changed?

00:58:50.500 --> 00:58:52.940
[Amit Varma]: Have you found new things to love?

00:58:52.940 --> 00:58:54.500
[Guest]: Earlier you could love one game.

00:58:54.500 --> 00:58:55.500
[Guest]: Now you can love three.

00:58:55.500 --> 00:58:56.500
[Guest]: Right.

00:58:56.500 --> 00:58:58.700
[Guest]: Earlier you could only love Test match cricket.

00:58:58.700 --> 00:58:59.940
[Guest]: Now you can love Test match cricket.

00:58:59.940 --> 00:59:02.940
[Guest]: You can love one day international cricket and you can love T20.

00:59:02.940 --> 00:59:07.620
[Guest]: You can have a Dhoni who never really enjoyed Test match cricket.

00:59:07.620 --> 00:59:13.500
[Guest]: In T20, he was a fine player, but Dhoni the one day cricketer, you now if there was no

00:59:13.500 --> 00:59:16.460
[Guest]: one day cricket, would we have seen the glory of Dhoni?

00:59:16.460 --> 00:59:19.420
[Guest]: Maybe the finest limited over one day player ever to play for India.

00:59:19.420 --> 00:59:20.660
[Guest]: Yeah, incredible.

00:59:20.660 --> 00:59:25.220
[Guest]: But would you have enjoyed Dhoni if you had not had that form of cricket?

00:59:25.220 --> 00:59:29.500
[Guest]: If we had only Test match cricket, would we have really appreciated the glory of Dhoni?

00:59:29.500 --> 00:59:33.820
[Guest]: If we had only T20, would Dhoni have been just one among other fantastic players?

00:59:33.820 --> 00:59:35.660
[Guest]: But ODI allowed you to do that.

00:59:35.660 --> 00:59:39.500
[Guest]: So cricket's now given us three things to drool over, to enjoy.

00:59:39.500 --> 00:59:41.300
[Guest]: Earlier it gave you only one.

00:59:41.300 --> 00:59:45.380
[Guest]: And you briefly referred earlier to how it's changed lives.

00:59:45.380 --> 00:59:51.420
[Guest]: The arrival of T20 has changed so many lower middle class Indian houses because earlier

00:59:51.420 --> 00:59:52.940
[Guest]: only 15 could play for India.

00:59:52.940 --> 00:59:54.820
[Guest]: 20 could aspire to play for India.

00:59:54.820 --> 00:59:56.780
[Guest]: Well, in the short list to play for India.

00:59:56.780 --> 00:59:58.620
[Guest]: And now 120 can make a career.

00:59:58.620 --> 01:00:01.540
[Guest]: If you can't, you'll get a couple of lakhs if you're a good player playing the Tamil

01:00:01.540 --> 01:00:02.540
[Guest]: Nadu Premier League.

01:00:02.540 --> 01:00:05.220
[Guest]: And then you break into the Ranji Trophy, you'll make another 8-10 lakhs if you're playing

01:00:05.220 --> 01:00:06.500
[Guest]: every game.

01:00:06.500 --> 01:00:09.460
[Guest]: So what the IPL has done is incredible.

01:00:09.460 --> 01:00:11.660
[Guest]: It's lifted people out from where they were.

01:00:11.660 --> 01:00:13.900
[Guest]: So I have a lot of time for IPL and ODI.

01:00:13.900 --> 01:00:16.540
[Guest]: But you're right.

01:00:16.540 --> 01:00:25.020
[Guest]: The arrival of colour television in the 80s, the liberalisation of the early 90s and the

01:00:25.020 --> 01:00:31.700
[Guest]: world T20 of 2007 that led to the arrival of the IPL would probably be the three biggest

01:00:31.700 --> 01:00:32.700
[Guest]: things.

01:00:32.700 --> 01:00:34.660
[Guest]: For Indian cricket, if you're going a little further back, of course, the arrival of Kerry

01:00:34.660 --> 01:00:35.660
[Guest]: Packer.

01:00:35.660 --> 01:00:36.660
[Guest]: Right.

01:00:36.660 --> 01:00:42.460
[Guest]: The arrival of Kerry Packer and the removal of those old fashioned ways of looking at

01:00:42.460 --> 01:00:46.220
[Guest]: test cricket where the player always, the player's finances came last.

01:00:46.220 --> 01:00:49.140
[Amit Varma]: I had a great episode with Gideon Hay and Prem Panikkar on that.

01:00:49.140 --> 01:00:52.540
[Amit Varma]: Gideon, of course, wrote a book about the whole Kerry Packer revolution and so on.

01:00:52.540 --> 01:00:56.940
[Amit Varma]: So we spoke about Kerry Packer and the IPL in a sense.

01:00:56.940 --> 01:01:00.140
[Amit Varma]: And you know, before the IPL started, there were lots of sceptics about how the game will

01:01:00.140 --> 01:01:01.140
[Amit Varma]: be corrupted.

01:01:01.140 --> 01:01:04.820
[Amit Varma]: And I remember writing a column in Cricket Friday that I'm arguing exactly the same things

01:01:04.820 --> 01:01:09.060
[Amit Varma]: that just in terms of the impact it's going to have the cricketers themselves, it is absurd

01:01:09.060 --> 01:01:13.940
[Amit Varma]: to oppose it, because it'll just make it the money will spread out so much, it'll finally

01:01:13.940 --> 01:01:14.940
[Amit Varma]: become...

01:01:14.940 --> 01:01:17.580
[Guest]: Amit, I read a lovely line.

01:01:17.580 --> 01:01:22.340
[Guest]: And if you heard this line from me before, pardon me, I read a lovely line about seven,

01:01:22.340 --> 01:01:23.340
[Guest]: eight years ago.

01:01:23.340 --> 01:01:28.980
[Guest]: And it said that influencers in society are always one generation behind reality.

01:01:28.980 --> 01:01:32.180
[Guest]: And you can see that in our game everywhere.

01:01:32.180 --> 01:01:37.660
[Guest]: The people who run our game are one generation behind the consumers of the game.

01:01:37.660 --> 01:01:42.740
[Guest]: Just as a consumer marketer in his 40s or 50s has to live with the challenge of knowing

01:01:42.740 --> 01:01:48.940
[Guest]: what a 20 something kid wants to buy, or a family that's earning 10,000 rupees a month

01:01:48.940 --> 01:01:52.900
[Guest]: in a family of six needs to do, he has to understand that.

01:01:52.900 --> 01:01:57.300
[Guest]: Similarly, the people running the game have to understand what the 20 somethings feel

01:01:57.300 --> 01:01:58.300
[Guest]: about the game.

01:01:58.300 --> 01:02:00.820
[Guest]: We can't say, ah, there's only girls and women, we don't care about them.

01:02:00.820 --> 01:02:04.160
[Guest]: No, they're now in what, almost 30% of your audience.

01:02:04.160 --> 01:02:05.960
[Guest]: So we're way behind.

01:02:05.960 --> 01:02:11.380
[Guest]: And so every time something new comes, people will say, ah, our game is no longer the same.

01:02:11.380 --> 01:02:13.780
[Guest]: It's the pyjama cricket, it's rescued cricket.

01:02:13.780 --> 01:02:16.660
[Guest]: T20 cricket came, rescued cricket.

01:02:16.660 --> 01:02:19.620
[Amit Varma]: And has this realization of the change filtered down to the commentary box?

01:02:19.620 --> 01:02:23.420
[Amit Varma]: I mean, if you look at the demographic profile of commentary boxes, you got a lot of old

01:02:23.420 --> 01:02:28.140
[Amit Varma]: people, you got the venerable Mr. Gavaskar in his 70s.

01:02:28.140 --> 01:02:32.100
[Amit Varma]: Have they kind of, was that a slow process where they began to figure out what's happening?

01:02:32.100 --> 01:02:33.540
[Guest]: Is there still a sense of denial?

01:02:33.540 --> 01:02:38.540
[Guest]: It's a very, no, I don't think they don't like T20 cricket.

01:02:38.540 --> 01:02:42.980
[Guest]: T20 cricket requires a very different kind of broadcast.

01:02:42.980 --> 01:02:46.620
[Guest]: In T20 cricket, you've got to keep pace with the action as well.

01:02:46.620 --> 01:02:51.820
[Guest]: Whereas in Test match cricket, sometimes you can just pause and let it go and the wind

01:02:51.820 --> 01:02:56.780
[Unknown]: is blowing by and oh, what a lovely, oh, I say, what a shot that was.

01:02:56.780 --> 01:02:59.180
[Guest]: In T20, you've got to be up there with the action.

01:02:59.180 --> 01:03:04.100
[Guest]: And so, and very often with the commercial intrusion, you have to say in 10 words what

01:03:04.100 --> 01:03:07.700
[Guest]: you would like to say in 40.

01:03:07.700 --> 01:03:10.820
[Guest]: So it's a very different kind of game.

01:03:10.820 --> 01:03:12.900
[Guest]: I absolutely enjoy doing it.

01:03:12.900 --> 01:03:15.420
[Guest]: If you ask me what is the one broadcast you'd like to do, it'd be the last four hours of

01:03:15.420 --> 01:03:17.020
[Guest]: a T20 game.

01:03:17.020 --> 01:03:18.980
[Guest]: Because that's when the excitement is building up.

01:03:18.980 --> 01:03:23.500
[Guest]: Every ball has, every ball is so critical.

01:03:23.500 --> 01:03:25.220
[Guest]: So it has changed, yes.

01:03:25.220 --> 01:03:27.900
[Guest]: But overall, broadcasting has changed.

01:03:27.900 --> 01:03:31.140
[Guest]: Producers are demanding different things from broadcasters than they did.

01:03:31.140 --> 01:03:34.060
[Guest]: It's still irritating to just repeat what you've just seen.

01:03:34.060 --> 01:03:39.140
[Guest]: But the game needs more storytellers than ever before, because someone's watching at

01:03:39.140 --> 01:03:44.820
[Guest]: home, he doesn't want a lesson in physics on a straight line on whether head is, whether

01:03:44.820 --> 01:03:46.900
[Guest]: knee is, whether toe is and see how it's moving.

01:03:46.900 --> 01:03:48.660
[Guest]: Yes, you need to know that.

01:03:48.660 --> 01:03:51.660
[Guest]: What the lady in Gulbarga is not interested.

01:03:51.660 --> 01:03:54.500
[Guest]: Lady in Gulbarga wants to know why is Virat Kohli getting it right?

01:03:54.500 --> 01:03:56.940
[Guest]: What is Virat Kohli going to do in this situation?

01:03:56.940 --> 01:03:58.340
[Guest]: So you need storytellers.

01:03:58.340 --> 01:04:02.780
[Guest]: And I'm overjoyed that this year, both Fox and Channel 7 in Australia post the Channel

01:04:02.780 --> 01:04:07.580
[Guest]: 9 rights transfer, have said we're going to go back the old television way, which is having

01:04:07.580 --> 01:04:09.420
[Guest]: callers and summarizers.

01:04:09.420 --> 01:04:13.220
[Guest]: The callers have seen the game for a long time, they place all the action in perspective,

01:04:13.220 --> 01:04:15.780
[Guest]: they don't tell you what is right or wrong.

01:04:15.780 --> 01:04:19.740
[Guest]: That they get the summarizer to say, or sometimes they say, oh, they're not a great ball.

01:04:19.740 --> 01:04:20.740
[Guest]: That's okay.

01:04:20.740 --> 01:04:26.260
[Guest]: But very clearly defined, cricket's the only sport that has gone all player, right?

01:04:26.260 --> 01:04:27.380
[Guest]: Football has callers.

01:04:27.380 --> 01:04:28.660
[Guest]: Football's the biggest game in the world.

01:04:28.660 --> 01:04:30.300
[Guest]: Football has callers.

01:04:30.300 --> 01:04:33.740
[Guest]: Every sport has callers because it's a completely different skill.

01:04:33.740 --> 01:04:38.140
[Guest]: It's a very different skill to be able to keep pace with the game, to be able to find

01:04:38.140 --> 01:04:40.140
[Guest]: the words for the narrative.

01:04:40.140 --> 01:04:48.380
[Guest]: I mean, without Tony Gregg's commentary on Desert Storm, would Tendulkar's innings have

01:04:48.380 --> 01:04:49.380
[Guest]: had the same impact?

01:04:49.380 --> 01:04:54.540
[Guest]: I mean, I remember when Tendulkar was, our post-season time, was doing that walk around

01:04:54.540 --> 01:04:55.540
[Guest]: the Wankhede Stadium.

01:04:55.540 --> 01:05:00.180
[Guest]: There's a producer, young producer of ours, he just nudged me and said, you.

01:05:00.180 --> 01:05:01.180
[Guest]: And I said, me?

01:05:01.180 --> 01:05:04.940
[Guest]: He said, yeah, you know, Sachin, since he was 14, you, you'll understand this moment

01:05:04.940 --> 01:05:05.940
[Guest]: better.

01:05:05.940 --> 01:05:10.620
[Guest]: And I got to describe that last moment of Tendulkar, and I could add all the feeling

01:05:10.620 --> 01:05:13.260
[Guest]: because I knew exactly what was going on through his mind.

01:05:13.260 --> 01:05:17.140
[Guest]: And Ian Bishop was sitting next to me, and he started, and I said, Ian?

01:05:17.140 --> 01:05:18.860
[Guest]: He said, no.

01:05:18.860 --> 01:05:23.620
[Guest]: But when Carlos Brathwaite hit the four sixes, nobody knew what it meant more than Ian Bishop

01:05:23.620 --> 01:05:24.620
[Guest]: did.

01:05:24.620 --> 01:05:27.100
[Guest]: And so Bishop was able to get the best words out.

01:05:27.100 --> 01:05:29.580
[Guest]: So you need, still need to be a storyteller.

01:05:29.580 --> 01:05:33.300
[Guest]: If you've played international cricket at the highest level, and you're an excellent

01:05:33.300 --> 01:05:37.460
[Guest]: storyteller without the ego to understand just what the man in the street wants, you

01:05:37.460 --> 01:05:40.880
[Guest]: have a huge advantage over someone like me who's not played the game.

01:05:40.880 --> 01:05:42.260
[Guest]: But sport needs storytellers.

01:05:42.260 --> 01:05:45.260
[Guest]: Jangal mein moor naacha, kisi ne na dekha.

01:05:45.260 --> 01:05:46.820
[Amit Varma]: And is it going to happen on television?

01:05:46.820 --> 01:05:51.420
[Amit Varma]: Because you know, a prototype of you, a young Harsha Bhogle, who is 16 years old today and

01:05:51.420 --> 01:05:56.100
[Amit Varma]: wants to get into commentary, he's not going to get in because it's all celebs and ex-cricketers

01:05:56.100 --> 01:05:57.100
[Amit Varma]: basically.

01:05:57.100 --> 01:06:00.860
[Amit Varma]: But other media he possibly can.

01:06:00.860 --> 01:06:05.540
[Guest]: And that is the next revolution that is coming, which is what we are doing.

01:06:05.540 --> 01:06:06.540
[Guest]: At Crickbuzz.

01:06:06.540 --> 01:06:08.260
[Guest]: Or what you and me are doing just now.

01:06:08.260 --> 01:06:09.420
[Guest]: Do a podcast.

01:06:09.420 --> 01:06:13.900
[Guest]: No force on earth can stop you from having your own channel.

01:06:13.900 --> 01:06:18.500
[Guest]: Digital is going to revolutionize it, already is around the world, is going to revolutionize

01:06:18.500 --> 01:06:20.220
[Guest]: opinion in sport.

01:06:20.220 --> 01:06:22.220
[Guest]: All along we were told, what's your batting average?

01:06:22.220 --> 01:06:24.020
[Guest]: You're not allowed to have an opinion.

01:06:24.020 --> 01:06:28.940
[Guest]: Now there's this kid coming out of college who knows every number in the world.

01:06:28.940 --> 01:06:31.860
[Guest]: And he's projecting those numbers through an algorithm.

01:06:31.860 --> 01:06:33.940
[Guest]: He's creating a predictive algorithm.

01:06:33.940 --> 01:06:36.540
[Guest]: And he's telling the expert, I think this is what's going to happen.

01:06:36.540 --> 01:06:40.020
[Guest]: And he's got as much chance of that coming right as the expert does.

01:06:40.020 --> 01:06:43.140
[Guest]: And so we will start having different kinds of broadcasts.

01:06:43.140 --> 01:06:45.180
[Guest]: I said that about three years ago.

01:06:45.180 --> 01:06:49.740
[Guest]: I said you must have for the very same match, four different kinds of broadcasts.

01:06:49.740 --> 01:06:53.340
[Guest]: You must have the expert, expert broadcast for the hardcore lover of the game.

01:06:53.340 --> 01:06:56.620
[Guest]: He wants to know technically what is happening, what is right, what's going on.

01:06:56.620 --> 01:07:00.780
[Guest]: You must have the storytellers broadcast, you must have the nerds broadcast.

01:07:00.780 --> 01:07:02.300
[Guest]: And you must have a broadcast with no commentary.

01:07:02.300 --> 01:07:06.220
[Amit Varma]: I mean, you can actually potentially have unlimited audio feeds, which you provide,

01:07:06.220 --> 01:07:09.020
[Amit Varma]: which people can watch along with the live images in front of them.

01:07:09.020 --> 01:07:10.700
[Guest]: So that is what people do in other countries.

01:07:10.700 --> 01:07:13.020
[Amit Varma]: They listen to the radio broadcast and watch the telecast.

01:07:13.020 --> 01:07:15.780
[Amit Varma]: And is that something you're excited to do going forward?

01:07:15.780 --> 01:07:17.740
[Guest]: I would be overjoyed by it.

01:07:17.740 --> 01:07:24.860
[Guest]: I mean, I see the talent among young people, young India today is an outrageously talented

01:07:24.860 --> 01:07:25.860
[Guest]: country.

01:07:25.860 --> 01:07:31.900
[Guest]: We have no right to tell a 17 year old kid who understands sports so well, because you

01:07:31.900 --> 01:07:35.620
[Guest]: don't have a batting average, you are not allowed to enter this community.

01:07:35.620 --> 01:07:37.820
[Guest]: This game belongs to all of us.

01:07:37.820 --> 01:07:38.820
[Guest]: What did we do first?

01:07:38.820 --> 01:07:41.740
[Guest]: We said you are not in the cities, you can't play the game.

01:07:41.740 --> 01:07:45.060
[Guest]: Then the people in small towns, we said you're a woman, you can't play the game.

01:07:45.060 --> 01:07:48.740
[Guest]: Then we said you're disabled, you're physically challenged, you cannot play the game.

01:07:48.740 --> 01:07:50.100
[Guest]: Says who?

01:07:50.100 --> 01:07:52.940
[Guest]: The visually challenged have a right to play the game.

01:07:52.940 --> 01:07:54.660
[Guest]: The deaf and dumb have a right to play the game.

01:07:54.660 --> 01:07:56.340
[Guest]: They're having their own World Cup.

01:07:56.340 --> 01:08:00.820
[Guest]: The Women's World Cup now is showing us, you watch Smriti Mandhana and Mithali Raj and

01:08:00.820 --> 01:08:02.620
[Amit Varma]: Armanpreet Kaur play.

01:08:02.620 --> 01:08:04.700
[Guest]: Who decided that they cannot play cricket?

01:08:04.700 --> 01:08:07.900
[Guest]: Similarly, who decided you cannot have an opinion on the game?

01:08:07.900 --> 01:08:10.860
[Guest]: The television networks will go box office and it's there.

01:08:10.860 --> 01:08:12.020
[Guest]: Shah Rukh Khan is box office.

01:08:12.020 --> 01:08:13.020
[Guest]: Aamir Khan is box office.

01:08:13.020 --> 01:08:15.180
[Guest]: You and me will never get to play that role.

01:08:15.180 --> 01:08:17.820
[Guest]: But digital is now allowing everybody to have a voice.

01:08:17.820 --> 01:08:21.460
[Guest]: And it's actually right for disruption.

01:08:21.460 --> 01:08:22.660
[Guest]: Absolutely.

01:08:22.660 --> 01:08:27.620
[Guest]: What's to stop two young kids, 18, 19 years old, to have a discussion on the game?

01:08:27.620 --> 01:08:28.620
[Guest]: That's exciting.

01:08:28.620 --> 01:08:34.420
[Guest]: They may not have the reach of television, but digital has a great way of just taking

01:08:34.420 --> 01:08:36.220
[Guest]: things to people that you never thought it would reach.

01:08:36.220 --> 01:08:37.820
[Guest]: Yeah, and what to find this on level?

01:08:37.820 --> 01:08:39.580
[Guest]: Who decides that you don't have an opinion?

01:08:39.580 --> 01:08:43.580
[Guest]: Earlier, there was a sub-editor who didn't allow your article to get published.

01:08:43.580 --> 01:08:45.300
[Guest]: And there was only one newspaper in each city.

01:08:45.300 --> 01:08:48.380
[Guest]: So if the sub-editor didn't like you, you published yourself.

01:08:48.380 --> 01:08:51.400
[Guest]: I mean, you wrote on the tree or something, whatever.

01:08:51.400 --> 01:08:53.500
[Guest]: Then came the television networks.

01:08:53.500 --> 01:08:57.100
[Guest]: And the television networks invest so much money in it, they have to go box office.

01:08:57.100 --> 01:08:58.660
[Guest]: They have no choice.

01:08:58.660 --> 01:09:00.140
[Guest]: It's like, I want to make a Shah Rukh Khan movie.

01:09:00.140 --> 01:09:02.940
[Guest]: My movie is already costing 100 and 200 crores.

01:09:02.940 --> 01:09:05.140
[Guest]: So I have to have the big stars in it.

01:09:05.140 --> 01:09:06.140
[Guest]: I have to have the masala.

01:09:06.140 --> 01:09:07.140
[Guest]: I have to have the song.

01:09:07.140 --> 01:09:08.540
[Guest]: I have to have whatever.

01:09:08.540 --> 01:09:10.620
[Guest]: But what are we seeing in cinema today?

01:09:10.620 --> 01:09:15.380
[Guest]: We are seeing Badhai Ho competing with the thugs of Hindustan.

01:09:15.380 --> 01:09:16.620
[Guest]: What is the comparison?

01:09:16.620 --> 01:09:17.900
[Guest]: That will happen in digital.

01:09:17.900 --> 01:09:22.140
[Guest]: We will get to a stage and I don't know what the law is, what the rights will be.

01:09:22.140 --> 01:09:26.180
[Guest]: We will get to a stage where there'll be young people sitting and having a ball, watching

01:09:26.180 --> 01:09:29.780
[Guest]: the telecast and people just following that soundtrack with the action.

01:09:29.780 --> 01:09:33.260
[Amit Varma]: And I hope some young people listening to this podcast now take inspiration from your

01:09:33.260 --> 01:09:34.260
[Amit Varma]: words.

01:09:34.260 --> 01:09:39.060
[Guest]: Yeah, I mean, sometimes I meet these young people and I say, what would I give to be

01:09:39.060 --> 01:09:41.140
[Guest]: 30 years younger today?

01:09:41.140 --> 01:09:45.980
[Guest]: They are, I mean, I see young India and I go, wow, just the sheer ability.

01:09:45.980 --> 01:09:46.980
[Guest]: This is inevitable.

01:09:46.980 --> 01:09:47.980
[Guest]: It will happen.

01:09:47.980 --> 01:09:51.540
[Guest]: And we cannot stand in the way of young people getting into broadcast and digital is going

01:09:51.540 --> 01:09:53.060
[Amit Varma]: to help them do that.

01:09:53.060 --> 01:09:57.660
[Amit Varma]: So I'll end this episode with sort of a final question that, you know, you've been with

01:09:57.660 --> 01:10:03.140
[Amit Varma]: cricket, you've been part of cricket for, you know, more than two and a half decades,

01:10:03.140 --> 01:10:05.060
[Amit Varma]: almost three decades.

01:10:05.060 --> 01:10:09.300
[Amit Varma]: What gives you hope about the future of the game and what causes you worry?

01:10:09.300 --> 01:10:13.140
[Guest]: This game has been written off so many times, just as India as a nation has been written

01:10:13.140 --> 01:10:15.260
[Guest]: off so many times and India bounces back.

01:10:15.260 --> 01:10:18.340
[Guest]: We are a powerful country at the moment.

01:10:18.340 --> 01:10:22.080
[Guest]: Cricket will never die because cricket is embedded in our thoughts.

01:10:22.080 --> 01:10:23.620
[Guest]: Cricket is embedded in our culture.

01:10:23.620 --> 01:10:29.140
[Guest]: The president of India goes to Australia and he is delivering cricketing parallels.

01:10:29.140 --> 01:10:31.460
[Guest]: Australia is trying to invest heavily into India.

01:10:31.460 --> 01:10:33.580
[Guest]: What do the two countries have in common?

01:10:33.580 --> 01:10:37.660
[Guest]: They did some research and they said the Kangaroo and Bradman are the two most known names across

01:10:37.660 --> 01:10:38.660
[Guest]: in India.

01:10:38.660 --> 01:10:42.780
[Guest]: Well, then it came to border, then it came to war, then it whatever, then it came to

01:10:42.780 --> 01:10:45.420
[Guest]: sledging, which is for better or worse.

01:10:45.420 --> 01:10:50.300
[Guest]: But cricket will never die out of India and T20 will take cricket to places that we never

01:10:50.300 --> 01:10:51.300
[Guest]: thought cricket would reach.

01:10:51.300 --> 01:10:55.900
[Guest]: It may not go to China, it may not go to the US, but we have to stop this obsession that

01:10:55.900 --> 01:10:59.280
[Guest]: everything in life has to go to China and the US.

01:10:59.280 --> 01:11:02.860
[Guest]: Cricket is being played in Fiji, in Papua New Guinea, there's 105 countries playing.

01:11:02.860 --> 01:11:06.780
[Guest]: T20 cricket will be the missionary that our game needed.

01:11:06.780 --> 01:11:10.060
[Guest]: Test cricket was, you know, stiff upper lips, a closed club.

01:11:10.060 --> 01:11:12.820
[Unknown]: Hello there, do you have your shoes tied properly?

01:11:12.820 --> 01:11:13.820
[Unknown]: No, you're out.

01:11:13.820 --> 01:11:15.500
[Unknown]: Oh, your jacket isn't buttoned.

01:11:15.500 --> 01:11:17.100
[Guest]: Only six of you can play the game.

01:11:17.100 --> 01:11:20.940
[Guest]: No, T20 will take it to 100 countries.

01:11:20.940 --> 01:11:26.700
[Guest]: And that I see T20 as a missionary of the game that will bring people in and then they

01:11:26.700 --> 01:11:29.940
[Guest]: will start to you know what this test cricket looks like an interesting thing.

01:11:29.940 --> 01:11:35.700
[Guest]: So for if you like test cricket, stop trampling on T20 cricket and realize that T20 cricket

01:11:35.700 --> 01:11:40.260
[Guest]: is the gateway that's going to draw people into your hidden into a hidden house right

01:11:40.260 --> 01:11:41.260
[Guest]: at the end.

01:11:41.260 --> 01:11:44.380
[Guest]: The two things that excite me the most of where T20 is taking cricket.

01:11:44.380 --> 01:11:45.380
[Guest]: Look at Afghanistan.

01:11:45.380 --> 01:11:46.380
[Guest]: Incredible.

01:11:46.380 --> 01:11:48.860
[Guest]: Oh, Rashid Khan was telling me the story.

01:11:48.860 --> 01:11:53.540
[Guest]: He said he went to a camp that his friend was running and he said, you know, famous,

01:11:53.540 --> 01:11:55.580
[Guest]: you must come and inaugurate my camp.

01:11:55.580 --> 01:11:57.980
[Guest]: So there were 126 bowlers there.

01:11:57.980 --> 01:11:58.980
[Guest]: Wow.

01:11:58.980 --> 01:12:03.260
[Guest]: 126 bowlers and he thought, you know, there'll be a left arm or there'll be a fast bowler.

01:12:03.260 --> 01:12:05.980
[Guest]: 126 leg spinners.

01:12:05.980 --> 01:12:11.460
[Guest]: 126 leg spinners growing up in Afghanistan, try and find me that hunger somewhere else.

01:12:11.460 --> 01:12:12.940
[Guest]: And did you think Afghanistan would do well?

01:12:12.940 --> 01:12:14.420
[Guest]: Do you think Oman would do well?

01:12:14.420 --> 01:12:19.700
[Guest]: You get Nepal, Sandeep Lamechani from Nepal comes and he's good enough to win an IPL contract

01:12:19.700 --> 01:12:21.820
[Guest]: and play for Delhi Daredevils.

01:12:21.820 --> 01:12:25.380
[Guest]: But we were not allowing the Nepal's and the Afghanistan's to play cricket because we said

01:12:25.380 --> 01:12:28.220
[Guest]: it's not for, you know, they can't.

01:12:28.220 --> 01:12:32.100
[Guest]: So for too long, cricket has prevented people from entering its fold.

01:12:32.100 --> 01:12:34.540
[Guest]: Cricket is to allow everybody into its fold.

01:12:34.540 --> 01:12:38.020
[Guest]: So I'm excited about what, where T20 will take our game.

01:12:38.020 --> 01:12:42.260
[Guest]: And I'm excited about the next generation of opinion makers that digital will allow

01:12:42.260 --> 01:12:47.580
[Guest]: in to break this closed field that the enormity of television is bound by.

01:12:47.580 --> 01:12:49.500
